19
00:03:55.058 --> 00:03:57.893
Burt! Shut that bloody thing off!

20
00:04:00.438 --> 00:04:01.730
Do you know what time it is?

21
00:04:01.898 --> 00:04:06.235
Burt! Burt!
You stupid old bastard!

22
00:04:06.403 --> 00:04:07.861
What do you think you're doing?

23
00:04:08.029 --> 00:04:10.072
Sorry, George. What'd you say?

24
00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:11.824
Do you know what time it is?

25
00:04:11.992 --> 00:04:14.576
I'm sorry. I've got a heck of a lot
to get done today.

26
00:04:14.744 --> 00:04:18.706
Right. And you know what they say,
the early bird catches the worm.

27
00:04:18.873 --> 00:04:22.835
Well, if you do this again one more time,
I'm calling the cops!

28
00:04:24.212 --> 00:04:26.588
And how about mowing your lawn?

29
00:04:26.756 --> 00:04:29.842
It's a bloody disgrace to the neighborhood.

30
00:04:34.097 --> 00:04:35.347
Yeah. All right.

31
00:04:42.355 --> 00:04:43.689
Hi, kid.

32
00:05:01.124 --> 00:05:05.419
Here we are. The perfect recipe.

33
00:05:05.587 --> 00:05:08.464
Two of Chevy...

34
00:05:08.631 --> 00:05:10.090
one of Ford.

35
00:05:14.012 --> 00:05:17.848
I think those '36 Chevy pistons...

36
00:05:18.016 --> 00:05:20.642
must have a touch of titanium
or something in them.

37
00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:23.437
They come out real good, you know?

38
00:05:23.605 --> 00:05:25.022
Hey, the kettle's boiling.

39
00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:27.816
Make yourself useful.
Make some tea.

40
00:05:33.281 --> 00:05:36.533
- Can we have a biscuit too?
- What?

41
00:05:36.701 --> 00:05:38.077
Can I have a ginger nat?

42
00:05:38.244 --> 00:05:40.788
Yeah. You know where they are.
Help yourself.

43
00:05:45.251 --> 00:05:47.961
No. You stay over there.
Stay there.

44
00:05:57.180 --> 00:05:59.389
- All right.
- What are you doing for Christmas, Burt?

45
00:05:59.557 --> 00:06:01.600
Christmas? I don't know. Why?

46
00:06:01.768 --> 00:06:03.769
Are you angling for a present or something?

47
00:06:03.937 --> 00:06:05.771
No. I wondered if you were going away.

48
00:06:05.939 --> 00:06:08.941
No. No time for Christmas, lad.

49
00:06:09.109 --> 00:06:11.026
Got a lot of work to do.

50
00:06:11.194 --> 00:06:13.862
I only managed 27 test runs this year.

51
00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:17.658
You know, 24 on the beach
and three on the road...

52
00:06:17.826 --> 00:06:19.743
all illegal like.

53
00:06:19.911 --> 00:06:23.413
I was going a bit over the speed limit,
I have to admit.

54
00:06:23.581 --> 00:06:25.916
- How fast were you going?
- I don't know. Haven't a clue.

55
00:06:26.084 --> 00:06:29.711
That's why I gotta get
it up to Bonneville...

56
00:06:29.879 --> 00:06:32.506
find out how fast she will go.

57
00:06:48.148 --> 00:06:49.481
Now, there you go.

58
00:06:50.233 --> 00:06:53.152
Go and get the piston out of the mold.

59
00:06:53.319 --> 00:06:55.028
Bob's your uncle.

60
00:06:55.196 --> 00:07:00.159
Now, this is the last part
of the operation...

61
00:07:00.326 --> 00:07:02.035
to chill the metal.

62
00:07:02.203 --> 00:07:03.745
It heat-treats it.

63
00:07:03.913 --> 00:07:05.998
All right. Watch yourself.

64
00:07:08.543 --> 00:07:10.669
That's where I got the water
for the kettle from.

65
00:07:10.837 --> 00:07:16.091
Yeah, well, that gives the tea
a nice tang of titanium, doesn't it?

66
00:07:16.259 --> 00:07:18.510
This bloke, he once asked me, he said:

67
00:07:18.678 --> 00:07:21.263
"How do you heat-treat
your pistons, Burt?"

68
00:07:21.431 --> 00:07:23.515
And I said, "I don't, mate.

69
00:07:23.683 --> 00:07:26.602
I just, you know, bang them in cold water
and Bob's your uncle."

70
00:07:26.769 --> 00:07:29.479
And he said, "Well, that's
the heat treatment," he said.

71
00:07:29.647 --> 00:07:33.108
And he just laughed and shook his head
and walked away like, and...

72
00:07:33.276 --> 00:07:36.695
Oh, Lord, this could be the perfect piston.

73
00:07:36.863 --> 00:07:39.364
It blooming well ought to be.
I've made hundreds of them.

74
00:07:39.532 --> 00:07:43.785
Look at them all up there,
all blown to smithereens.

75
00:07:43.953 --> 00:07:45.621
You made all those?

76
00:07:45.788 --> 00:07:47.623
Yeah, I did. Look. Perfect.

77
00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:50.125
Beautiful. No inclusion, see?

78
00:07:50.293 --> 00:07:55.547
Tommy, does your mother have
a carving knife I could borrow?

79
00:07:55.715 --> 00:07:56.965
A carving knife? Yeah.

80
00:07:57.133 --> 00:07:59.218
Yeah. We need a good, sharp knife.

81
00:08:04.641 --> 00:08:08.769
Okay. All right. Hang on.

82
00:08:08.937 --> 00:08:10.604
Thomas, what are you up to?

83
00:08:10.772 --> 00:08:13.148
Nothing, mom. Can I have some
bread and peanut butter?

84
00:08:13.316 --> 00:08:16.735
Okay, but make sure you put everything
away when you've finished.

85
00:08:17.237 --> 00:08:18.946
Sorry about that. Yeah.

86
00:08:23.326 --> 00:08:24.326
Really?

87
00:08:27.372 --> 00:08:30.749
Tom, don't forget the wood.

88
00:08:30.917 --> 00:08:33.001
No, Mom.

89
00:08:36.965 --> 00:08:39.007
All right.

90
00:08:39.175 --> 00:08:44.054
I have to get as much
rubber off as possible.

91
00:08:44.222 --> 00:08:47.224
It has to be perfectly bald
like that, you see?

92
00:08:47.392 --> 00:08:49.893
- Why's that?
- Well, at high speed...

93
00:08:50.061 --> 00:08:55.065
the centrifugal force expands the tire...

94
00:08:55.233 --> 00:09:00.529
and it rubs against the frame of the bike.

95
00:09:00.697 --> 00:09:03.198
Have to be careful not to cut
through the cords, though.

96
00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:08.829
- Why do you pee on your lemon tree?
- What?

97
00:09:08.997 --> 00:09:12.374
Why do you pee on your lemon tree?

98
00:09:14.294 --> 00:09:15.711
Who says I do that?

99
00:09:15.878 --> 00:09:18.922
Mom says she sees you every morning.
She goes on and on about it.

100
00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:20.132
Oh, does she?

101
00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:22.301
Yeah? Oh, well.

102
00:09:22.468 --> 00:09:24.428
Well, it's good fertilizer, you know.

103
00:09:24.595 --> 00:09:27.639
You shouldn't waste anything
in this world, sonny.

104
00:09:27.807 --> 00:09:30.225
- Well, I better be off home.
- All right, then.

105
00:09:30.393 --> 00:09:32.561
Mom gets a bit cross
if I stay over here too long.

106
00:09:32.729 --> 00:09:35.397
She does? Well...

107
00:09:35.732 --> 00:09:37.316
Are you finished with the knife?

108
00:09:37.483 --> 00:09:40.652
Not yet. I'll drop it by later.

109
00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:43.947
No. Don't do that. I'll pick it up
after school tomorrow.

110
00:09:44.115 --> 00:09:45.615
All right.

111
00:09:46.659 --> 00:09:50.078
- Bye!
- Cheerio!

112
00:09:57.503 --> 00:09:59.087
- Burt Munro.
- Yeah?

113
00:09:59.255 --> 00:10:02.424
- I believe you have my carving knife.
- Oh, yes.

114
00:10:02.592 --> 00:10:05.260
- And my sharpener.
- Yeah.

115
00:10:05.428 --> 00:10:08.221
Oh, here we are.

116
00:10:09.432 --> 00:10:13.310
Here. Well, thanks a lot, love.

117
00:10:22.445 --> 00:10:24.905
- Good day, Frank, how are you?
- Oh, not bad.

118
00:10:25.073 --> 00:10:27.115
- It could be better, it could be worse.
- Good.

119
00:10:27.283 --> 00:10:30.619
I see your front tire's gone
a bit flat on you there, Burt.

120
00:10:30.787 --> 00:10:33.789
Oh, yeah. Well, the good news is
it's only flat on the bottom.

121
00:10:33.956 --> 00:10:35.957
I'll see you tomorrow night
for the fun and games.

122
00:10:36.125 --> 00:10:37.459
All right. It'll be a good one.

123
00:10:40.129 --> 00:10:42.547
Hello, Fran. Uh...

124
00:10:42.715 --> 00:10:44.758
Give us the lot, will you? The usual.

125
00:10:44.926 --> 00:10:47.177
One pension check coming up.

126
00:10:47.345 --> 00:10:51.431
Fran, I want to ask you a question...

127
00:10:51.599 --> 00:10:53.809
the answer to which is...

128
00:10:53.976 --> 00:10:56.311
you know, a definite yes.

129
00:10:56.479 --> 00:10:58.188
All right. Ready?

130
00:10:58.356 --> 00:11:03.235
All right. Yes.
What's the question, Burt?

131
00:11:03.403 --> 00:11:05.904
Would you feel inclined to, you know...

132
00:11:06.072 --> 00:11:08.907
accompany an impeccable young gentleman...

133
00:11:09.075 --> 00:11:12.452
to a local do tomorrow night?

134
00:11:13.413 --> 00:11:16.540
Are you asking me on a date, Burt Munro?

135
00:11:16.707 --> 00:11:19.000
Well, yeah, I suppose I am,
actually, aren't I?

136
00:11:20.336 --> 00:11:22.838
- Would you?
- You're on.

137
00:11:29.345 --> 00:11:31.304
- Hello, son.
- Hey, Burt.

138
00:11:32.056 --> 00:11:33.682
That's disgusting!

139
00:11:33.850 --> 00:11:36.643
Yeah. It is, isn't it?

140
00:11:36.811 --> 00:11:41.398
I'm all dressed up for the do tonight
and I couldn't get my best shoes on...

141
00:11:41.566 --> 00:11:44.776
because my toenails
had grown like oyster shells.

142
00:11:44.944 --> 00:11:49.322
Anyway, this should do the trick.

143
00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:50.907
There. Look at that.

144
00:11:51.075 --> 00:11:52.534
Little twinkle-toes.

145
00:11:59.625 --> 00:12:02.711
- Thanks, Burt.
- Right-o.

146
00:12:07.884 --> 00:12:11.219
- Hey, Burt!
- Hi.

147
00:12:11.387 --> 00:12:13.054
- Evening, Burt.
- Thank you. Thank you.

148
00:12:13.222 --> 00:12:15.182
- This is Fran.
- Hi, Fran.

149
00:12:15.349 --> 00:12:17.017
Thank you very much.

150
00:12:17.185 --> 00:12:19.728
- Hello, Duncan!
- Burt!

151
00:12:19.896 --> 00:12:23.648
I'm just gonna say hello to the lads
and then I'll be back in a second, love.

152
00:12:23.816 --> 00:12:25.734
Hello, Pete. Hello, Graham.

153
00:12:25.902 --> 00:12:27.986
- You doing well?
- Yeah. Not bad.

154
00:12:28.946 --> 00:12:30.739
- Happy birthday, Burt.
- Thanks a lot, mate.

155
00:12:30.907 --> 00:12:33.909
- This is a bit of a surprise, isn't it?
- Hey, Burt.

156
00:12:34.076 --> 00:12:36.411
Would you like to buy
a raffle ticket or two?

157
00:12:36.579 --> 00:12:37.996
What's it for?

158
00:12:38.164 --> 00:12:40.040
Porky the pig, plus two dozen beers.

159
00:12:40.208 --> 00:12:42.083
We're raising money
to send Burt to the U.S.A.

160
00:12:42.251 --> 00:12:44.002
Our mate Burt.

161
00:12:45.421 --> 00:12:48.381
- Come on, Burt. Come and dance.
- Hello, love.

162
00:12:48.549 --> 00:12:52.093
- What's this? The twist?
- This is the twist. You know the twist?

163
00:12:52.261 --> 00:12:55.305
- No.
- Come twist with me.

164
00:12:57.308 --> 00:12:59.142
See? You can twist.

165
00:13:02.021 --> 00:13:03.939
That's it, that's it.

166
00:13:05.608 --> 00:13:08.318
When the air clears
And the dust settles down

167
00:13:08.486 --> 00:13:11.613
You look outside
Have they leveled the town?

168
00:13:11.781 --> 00:13:16.076
But there in the yard So briskly alive

169
00:13:16.244 --> 00:13:21.081
Stands Burt Munro's
Trusty old Indian Scout 45

170
00:13:23.334 --> 00:13:25.377
Thank you, mate.

171
00:13:25.962 --> 00:13:29.798
That was a wonderful tribute to Burt.
Now, come on, Burt.

172
00:13:29.966 --> 00:13:31.132
We want you up on stage.

173
00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:34.302
Come on, come on. Up you come.

174
00:13:36.889 --> 00:13:40.475
And I hope all of you have bought
a raffle ticket tonight...

175
00:13:40.643 --> 00:13:44.771
because we believe Burt will put
the Southland Motorcycle Club...

176
00:13:44.939 --> 00:13:46.856
on the map!

177
00:13:56.576 --> 00:13:58.159
What's going on out there?

178
00:13:58.828 --> 00:14:01.329
Get out of here!

179
00:14:02.331 --> 00:14:04.958
- Oh, dear.
- What's this?

180
00:14:10.798 --> 00:14:14.718
Well, folks, it looks like I've cracked it.
I've, you know...

181
00:14:14.885 --> 00:14:16.261
You Burt Munro?

182
00:14:16.429 --> 00:14:18.430
The, uh... What'd he say?

183
00:14:18.598 --> 00:14:19.723
I said, are you Burt Munro?

184
00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:22.017
Are you looking for old Burt?

185
00:14:22.184 --> 00:14:24.019
Why, no. Have you
seen Burt anywhere?

186
00:14:25.479 --> 00:14:27.856
Anyone seen Burt? Well, no...

187
00:14:28.024 --> 00:14:29.107
You are. You're Burt Munro.

188
00:14:29.275 --> 00:14:31.359
You're the old codger that rides
the Army Indian.

189
00:14:31.527 --> 00:14:35.030
Oh, that old joker. Burt Munro, yeah.

190
00:14:35.197 --> 00:14:37.032
Yeah, that's me, I think. Oh, yeah.

191
00:14:37.199 --> 00:14:41.411
Now, the... Young fellow,
the Army Indian is a real dog.

192
00:14:41.579 --> 00:14:45.332
What I've got is the genuine article...

193
00:14:45.499 --> 00:14:48.877
the 1920 V-twin Scout.

194
00:14:49.045 --> 00:14:50.629
That's the one with the pedals, right?

195
00:14:52.173 --> 00:14:53.673
- Yeah, right.
- Good job, Burt.

196
00:14:53.841 --> 00:14:58.637
Well, I don't know what sort of push bikes
you monkeys came here into town on...

197
00:14:58.804 --> 00:15:03.975
but I know that my old-timer would thrash
the backsides off whatever they are.

198
00:15:04.143 --> 00:15:05.602
No, I don't think so, grandad.

199
00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:09.314
No? Why don't you chumps...

200
00:15:09.482 --> 00:15:11.900
put your money where your mouth is, then?

201
00:15:12.068 --> 00:15:14.569
You're on, you old coot.

202
00:15:15.613 --> 00:15:17.697
Right. Yeah.

203
00:15:17.865 --> 00:15:20.075
- Looks like they've chickened out, Burt.
- What?

204
00:15:20.242 --> 00:15:21.618
Looks like they've chickened out.

205
00:15:21.786 --> 00:15:23.745
- They're here.
- What?

206
00:15:23.913 --> 00:15:25.538
They're here.

207
00:15:29.877 --> 00:15:31.586
It's nice of them to show up, isn't it?

208
00:15:39.220 --> 00:15:41.888
A hundred says the Indian comes last.

209
00:15:42.056 --> 00:15:43.264
Right, mate.

210
00:16:06.288 --> 00:16:07.288
Come on!

211
00:16:12.128 --> 00:16:14.295
Go!

212
00:16:17.758 --> 00:16:19.426
Come on! Give me a push!

213
00:16:21.721 --> 00:16:23.513
- Now you're talking!
- Come on, Burt!

214
00:16:23.681 --> 00:16:24.806
Give me a push!

215
00:16:24.974 --> 00:16:27.058
Come on, push hard!

216
00:16:28.769 --> 00:16:30.478
Go, Burt!

217
00:16:32.606 --> 00:16:33.857
Go, Burt!

218
00:16:35.276 --> 00:16:36.901
Come on! Go!

219
00:17:20.571 --> 00:17:22.197
Bugger.

220
00:17:22.364 --> 00:17:23.948
Nice bike, grandad.

221
00:17:24.116 --> 00:17:25.950
Loser!

222
00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:28.036
Yee-ha!

223
00:17:43.260 --> 00:17:45.887
- Well, thanks, fellas.
- Better luck next time.

224
00:17:46.055 --> 00:17:47.722
- Yeah.
- Bad luck, Burt.

225
00:17:52.561 --> 00:17:54.771
Here you go. Oh, thanks, love.

226
00:17:54.939 --> 00:17:56.314
- Careful, it's hot.
- All right.

227
00:17:58.067 --> 00:18:01.402
Well, at least I gave them
a good run for their money.

228
00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:04.239
On the downward leg, anyway.

229
00:18:04.406 --> 00:18:07.617
Burt, what's it gonna cost
to get over to America?

230
00:18:07.785 --> 00:18:09.410
Sorry, love. What'd you say?

231
00:18:09.578 --> 00:18:12.038
How much is it gonna cost
to get over to America?

232
00:18:12.206 --> 00:18:15.458
Oh, I don't know. About 2000, I'm told.

233
00:18:15.626 --> 00:18:17.252
And how much money have you got now?

234
00:18:18.087 --> 00:18:21.047
Well, apart from today's disaster...

235
00:18:21.215 --> 00:18:23.174
and the dough from last night...

236
00:18:23.342 --> 00:18:26.719
and the pension money I've been saving...

237
00:18:26.887 --> 00:18:32.141
about 1275 dollars,
United States dollars, I reckon.

238
00:18:32.309 --> 00:18:34.269
Well, I could lend you some money.

239
00:18:34.436 --> 00:18:38.565
Oh, that's very kind of you, Fran,
but, no, I couldn't do that, love.

240
00:18:38.732 --> 00:18:39.941
No. Thanks.

241
00:18:40.109 --> 00:18:42.652
Well, there must be something you can do.

242
00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:44.779
Well, I haven't told
anyone else this, Fran...

243
00:18:44.947 --> 00:18:48.449
but I don't reckon
I'll be going to Bonneville.

244
00:18:48.617 --> 00:18:49.951
I mean, not this year, anyway.

245
00:18:50.119 --> 00:18:55.248
And, you know, $700
is a lot of money to find...

246
00:18:55.416 --> 00:18:58.793
and the boat leaves in five days...

247
00:18:58.961 --> 00:19:01.629
but, you know...

248
00:19:01.797 --> 00:19:06.092
Except I would like to see
how fast she'll really go...

249
00:19:06.260 --> 00:19:09.095
before I fall off the perch, as it were...

250
00:19:09.263 --> 00:19:12.140
before I, you know, kick the old bucket.

251
00:19:12.308 --> 00:19:14.058
Oh, well. Huh.

252
00:19:21.817 --> 00:19:23.234
Hello, Lloyd.

253
00:19:23.402 --> 00:19:25.987
Good day, Burt.
Shame about the fall.

254
00:19:26.155 --> 00:19:28.323
Yeah, well, I'm still
in one piece, aren't I?

255
00:19:28.490 --> 00:19:30.325
Yeah. What are you having tonight?

256
00:19:30.492 --> 00:19:33.286
Specialty of the house, Pea, Pie 'n' Pudd.

257
00:19:33.454 --> 00:19:35.496
- It's 5 bob.
- All right.

258
00:19:35.664 --> 00:19:36.664
- Burt.
- Yeah?

259
00:19:36.832 --> 00:19:39.083
Why don't you take out
a mortgage on your house?

260
00:19:39.251 --> 00:19:41.085
- What house?
- Oh, your property.

261
00:19:41.253 --> 00:19:42.879
I mean, it's worth something.

262
00:19:43.047 --> 00:19:46.007
Yeah. Here you are.

263
00:19:46.175 --> 00:19:48.593
Burt Munro, look at
the color of your hands.

264
00:19:48.761 --> 00:19:51.321
- What's the matter with them?
- You're gonna wash those mitts...

265
00:19:51.388 --> 00:19:53.348
before you put them anywhere near me.

266
00:19:53.515 --> 00:19:55.516
Here we are.

267
00:20:28.092 --> 00:20:30.259
Wakey, wakey.

268
00:20:30.427 --> 00:20:35.014
Time to rise and shine.

269
00:20:35.182 --> 00:20:38.559
Oh, Burt, you're a sweetie.

270
00:20:38.727 --> 00:20:41.312
Gotta get out of here before
the neighbors spot me.

271
00:20:46.402 --> 00:20:47.902
Oh, Burt.

272
00:20:48.070 --> 00:20:50.446
This tastes a bit odd.

273
00:20:50.614 --> 00:20:51.906
Metallic.

274
00:20:56.370 --> 00:20:59.247
- Oh. Crikey. Oh.
- What?

275
00:20:59.415 --> 00:21:02.375
I've got a pain in my chest. Ah.

276
00:21:03.085 --> 00:21:05.420
He's in the shed! Hurry!

277
00:21:09.591 --> 00:21:12.593
Mom, Dad, something happened to Burt!

278
00:21:19.601 --> 00:21:21.310
Burt, what's wrong with you?

279
00:21:21.478 --> 00:21:24.313
I'll be all right, Tommy.
Don't worry about me.

280
00:21:24.481 --> 00:21:26.607
- Are you sure?
- Yeah.

281
00:21:47.796 --> 00:21:49.839
What are you all staring at?

282
00:21:50.007 --> 00:21:51.758
Dirty old men need love too.

283
00:21:55.971 --> 00:21:57.847
- Mr. Munro.
- Hello.

284
00:21:58.015 --> 00:22:00.516
So, what's the story, doc?

285
00:22:00.684 --> 00:22:02.518
I'm sorry. It's not good news.

286
00:22:02.686 --> 00:22:05.104
Oh, yeah? Well, fire away.

287
00:22:06.440 --> 00:22:09.150
- You've had an attack of angina.
- Oh, yeah?

288
00:22:09.318 --> 00:22:11.069
You have arteriosclerosis.

289
00:22:11.904 --> 00:22:13.196
What's that?

290
00:22:13.363 --> 00:22:15.948
It's a narrowing of the arteries
from the heart.

291
00:22:16.116 --> 00:22:17.492
Oh, dear.

292
00:22:17.659 --> 00:22:19.459
I'm afraid there's
not too much we can do...

293
00:22:19.536 --> 00:22:22.056
for you at your age other than
suggesting you take it easy.

294
00:22:22.164 --> 00:22:23.331
Oh, yeah?

295
00:22:23.499 --> 00:22:26.379
Look, if you have another attack,
pop one of these under your tongue...

296
00:22:26.502 --> 00:22:29.003
let it dissolve
and then swallow the saliva.

297
00:22:29.171 --> 00:22:31.339
The pain should be gone in 30 seconds.

298
00:22:31.507 --> 00:22:32.840
What do you call these things?

299
00:22:33.008 --> 00:22:34.634
- Trinitrate pills.
- Yeah?

300
00:22:34.802 --> 00:22:36.511
Better known as nitroglycerine.

301
00:22:36.678 --> 00:22:38.930
Oh, yeah. The stuff you
blow things up with.

302
00:22:39.098 --> 00:22:41.891
- Yes, but in much smaller quantities.
- Yeah. All right.

303
00:22:42.059 --> 00:22:47.105
Will this have any effect
on me riding my bike?

304
00:22:48.690 --> 00:22:52.110
Unfortunately, I think your
motorcycling days are over.

305
00:22:52.277 --> 00:22:53.820
Like hell they are.

306
00:23:08.293 --> 00:23:10.586
It won't be much longer.

307
00:23:18.053 --> 00:23:21.389
Springfield. Springfield.

308
00:23:22.099 --> 00:23:25.226
- That's where the Indians come from.
- Indians?

309
00:23:25.394 --> 00:23:29.730
Yeah, the Indians from Springfield,
Massachusetts.

310
00:23:29.898 --> 00:23:32.567
It's the world's greatest motorcycle.

311
00:23:32.734 --> 00:23:35.194
- Oh, is that so?
- That's right.

312
00:23:36.822 --> 00:23:39.157
- You can come through now.
- All right. Thank you.

313
00:23:39.324 --> 00:23:41.659
Yeah. Springfield.

314
00:23:43.745 --> 00:23:47.206
You know, the plan is for me
to drive up to Timaru...

315
00:23:47.374 --> 00:23:51.085
and there, me and my bike will
catch a boat to the U.S. of A...

316
00:23:51.253 --> 00:23:55.590
to Los Angeles,
and the boat leaves on Saturday...

317
00:23:55.757 --> 00:23:58.467
and I'll buy a car in Los Angeles...

318
00:23:58.635 --> 00:24:01.095
and drive up to Utah
to the Bonneville Salt Flats.

319
00:24:01.263 --> 00:24:04.056
- And it's really important you do this trip?
- Sure is, mate.

320
00:24:04.224 --> 00:24:06.601
You know, ever since I was a lad...

321
00:24:06.768 --> 00:24:09.128
I've been interested in things
that go fast, you know?

322
00:24:09.229 --> 00:24:13.941
Things that roll and go, and, you know,
at Bonneville, things go real fast.

323
00:24:14.109 --> 00:24:18.654
It's, you know,
this giant, dried-up lake bed...

324
00:24:18.822 --> 00:24:21.324
and it goes for miles and miles
and it's dead flat...

325
00:24:21.491 --> 00:24:25.161
and you can drive a vehicle
just as fast as it will go...

326
00:24:25.329 --> 00:24:28.456
and it's one of the few places on Earth...

327
00:24:28.624 --> 00:24:33.044
where you can find out just
what your machine is capable of.

328
00:24:33.212 --> 00:24:35.171
In fact, here I'm on the...

329
00:24:35.339 --> 00:24:38.090
That's me on the front of
the New Zealand Motor Cyclist.

330
00:24:38.258 --> 00:24:39.926
- That's the Indian there.
- Very good.

331
00:24:40.093 --> 00:24:43.387
Yeah, a few years ago.
So I'd best be off soon...

332
00:24:43.555 --> 00:24:46.275
because I don't know how much longer
I've got to live, you see.

333
00:24:46.308 --> 00:24:48.309
Well, I don't think I heard
that last statement.

334
00:24:48.477 --> 00:24:49.810
I said, I don't know how much...

335
00:24:49.978 --> 00:24:52.772
- Yeah. I heard you the first time.
- Oh.

336
00:24:52.940 --> 00:24:54.357
So, tell me, Burt...

337
00:24:54.524 --> 00:24:57.318
what are you offering
as collateral for this loan?

338
00:24:57.486 --> 00:24:59.987
Well, my tools and my bits 'n' pieces...

339
00:25:00.155 --> 00:25:02.155
and my trophies
and a lot of things like that.

340
00:25:02.282 --> 00:25:04.602
Well, I don't think they'd be
of much interest to the bank.

341
00:25:04.743 --> 00:25:07.245
I think we'd be looking for
something more substantial...

342
00:25:07.412 --> 00:25:10.665
something like the deed of title
to your property?

343
00:25:12.292 --> 00:25:16.254
- Did you get the money?
- Yep. Off on Thursday.

344
00:25:16.421 --> 00:25:17.505
- Thursday.
- Yeah.

345
00:25:17.673 --> 00:25:19.757
That soon? I wish I could come too.

346
00:25:19.925 --> 00:25:21.801
Maybe next time.

347
00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:26.347
Thomas, it's dinnertime.
Come home now.

348
00:25:26.515 --> 00:25:28.140
Nearly finished, Mrs. Jackson.

349
00:25:28.308 --> 00:25:31.185
- Yeah, Mom, we're almost finished.
- Thomas.

350
00:25:32.938 --> 00:25:34.897
See you after dinner, Burt.

351
00:25:35.065 --> 00:25:36.983
All right, lad.

352
00:25:44.491 --> 00:25:46.158
Hey, not so fast!

353
00:25:46.326 --> 00:25:48.661
I'm the record-breaker.

354
00:25:50.956 --> 00:25:52.540
Where are you going?

355
00:25:54.084 --> 00:25:56.043
And that's the...

356
00:25:56.211 --> 00:25:59.714
Before I put the...
You know, the streamliner on it.

357
00:26:03.510 --> 00:26:04.677
What's that one?

358
00:26:05.554 --> 00:26:08.139
Yeah. That's a girlfriend of mine...

359
00:26:08.307 --> 00:26:11.684
when I first bought the bike,
a long time ago, that was.

360
00:26:13.437 --> 00:26:14.437
Yeah.

361
00:26:14.604 --> 00:26:17.189
Aren't you scared
you'll kill yourself if you crash?

362
00:26:17.357 --> 00:26:18.899
No.

363
00:26:19.067 --> 00:26:25.156
No, you live more in five minutes
on a bike like this, going flat out...

364
00:26:25.324 --> 00:26:27.616
than some people live in their lifetime.

365
00:26:27.784 --> 00:26:32.496
And... Yeah, more in five minutes...

366
00:26:32.664 --> 00:26:34.248
That's my dad there.

367
00:26:35.208 --> 00:26:37.084
And my mom.

368
00:26:38.253 --> 00:26:40.254
They've all gone.

369
00:26:41.506 --> 00:26:43.966
It's gone by so fast.

370
00:26:44.760 --> 00:26:47.386
No. Danger is the spice of life...

371
00:26:47.554 --> 00:26:50.890
and you've got to take a risk
now and again, haven't you, son?

372
00:26:51.058 --> 00:26:55.102
Yeah, that's what makes life worthwhile.

373
00:26:55.270 --> 00:26:58.564
And, you know, having
some nice ladies around...

374
00:26:58.732 --> 00:27:00.858
can be a big help, mind you.

375
00:27:02.235 --> 00:27:06.781
- You really don't get scared?
- No. No.

376
00:27:06.948 --> 00:27:09.992
You know, when I was
a boy about your age...

377
00:27:10.160 --> 00:27:14.121
I had a little twin brother.
His name was Ernie.

378
00:27:14.289 --> 00:27:17.541
And one day, our dad was out in the back...

379
00:27:17.709 --> 00:27:19.794
cutting down a tree...

380
00:27:19.961 --> 00:27:24.965
and suddenly it got hung up...
The tree, that is.

381
00:27:25.133 --> 00:27:28.594
It got stuck or something,
and Ernie went to try and help...

382
00:27:28.762 --> 00:27:33.808
and all of a sudden,
the tree slipped and fell on him...

383
00:27:33.975 --> 00:27:35.935
and killed him stone dead.

384
00:27:38.939 --> 00:27:40.689
Yeah.

385
00:27:40.857 --> 00:27:42.733
I'll always remember that.

386
00:27:42.901 --> 00:27:44.985
Anyway, since then...

387
00:27:45.153 --> 00:27:48.155
I've always tried never
to be scared of anything.

388
00:27:48.698 --> 00:27:51.158
Though I must say,
before a big bike event...

389
00:27:51.326 --> 00:27:53.452
I do sometimes get nervous, you know.

390
00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:58.374
If the butterflies
in my stomach were cows...

391
00:27:58.542 --> 00:28:03.003
I'd be able to start a dairy farm.

392
00:28:03.171 --> 00:28:05.798
Right. That's funny.

393
00:28:06.508 --> 00:28:10.719
When they took you off in the ambulance
to the hospital, what happened?

394
00:28:10.887 --> 00:28:13.514
I don't know. It was just a touch
of indigestion, I think.

395
00:28:13.682 --> 00:28:16.016
Yeah, that's all it was.
There's nothing wrong with me.

396
00:28:16.184 --> 00:28:17.685
Don't you worry about me.

397
00:28:17.853 --> 00:28:19.353
And anyway, at my age...

398
00:28:19.521 --> 00:28:23.065
any day above ground and vertical
is a good day.

399
00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:26.861
Listen, you take care of this
until I get back, all right?

400
00:28:27.612 --> 00:28:29.155
What happens if you don't come back?

401
00:28:29.322 --> 00:28:32.032
Well, we'll talk about that then,
shan't we?

402
00:28:34.202 --> 00:28:35.661
- Hey, Burt.
- Yeah?

403
00:28:35.829 --> 00:28:37.872
- Don't forget to mow your lawns, will you?
- What?

404
00:28:38.039 --> 00:28:41.375
Don't forget to mow your lawns.
My dad goes on and on about it.

405
00:28:41.626 --> 00:28:42.835
Oh, he does, does he?

406
00:28:43.003 --> 00:28:45.713
He says it lowers the property values
of the neighborhood.

407
00:28:47.966 --> 00:28:51.302
Well, oh, dear, we can't have that, can we?

408
00:29:14.367 --> 00:29:15.743
What are you doing?

409
00:29:15.911 --> 00:29:18.746
Hello, son! I was just getting rid
of the grass!

410
00:29:20.832 --> 00:29:23.417
Burt, what the hell
are you doing this time?

411
00:29:23.585 --> 00:29:27.463
Well, like you said, George,
I'm getting rid of the grass...

412
00:29:27.631 --> 00:29:30.257
being a good neighbor
before I leave tomorrow.

413
00:29:30.425 --> 00:29:35.346
Tom. Tom! Get back inside now. Now!

414
00:29:36.515 --> 00:29:37.890
Honestly, Burt.

415
00:29:41.937 --> 00:29:44.939
- What are they doing here?
- It might be the fire, Burt.

416
00:29:53.615 --> 00:29:56.158
All right. The tire goes in first.

417
00:29:56.326 --> 00:29:58.118
That's it.

418
00:29:58.286 --> 00:30:01.121
That's it. You got it.

419
00:30:01.289 --> 00:30:02.957
Screw it in here.

420
00:30:04.543 --> 00:30:06.293
Pills.

421
00:30:06.461 --> 00:30:08.587
My papers and passport.

422
00:30:08.755 --> 00:30:12.132
All right. See if I've got everything.

423
00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:16.053
My spectacles, testicles, watch and wallet.

424
00:30:16.221 --> 00:30:17.638
What are you laughing at?

425
00:30:17.806 --> 00:30:20.849
- I'm on my way.
- Dad says to call us collect.

426
00:30:21.017 --> 00:30:23.477
- What?
- Dad says to call us collect.

427
00:30:23.645 --> 00:30:24.645
That's nice of him.

428
00:30:24.813 --> 00:30:27.356
- Tell us how you get on.
- All right. Thank you.

429
00:30:27.524 --> 00:30:29.233
That's our phone number.

430
00:30:30.569 --> 00:30:32.528
Do you think you'll break the record?

431
00:30:32.696 --> 00:30:34.863
Well, I hope so. Yeah.

432
00:30:35.031 --> 00:30:36.865
Dad doesn't think you can do it.

433
00:30:37.951 --> 00:30:39.702
Oh, is that what he said?

434
00:30:40.870 --> 00:30:42.496
He says everyone thinks that.

435
00:30:43.373 --> 00:30:45.124
Oh, well.

436
00:30:46.084 --> 00:30:47.334
Except me.

437
00:30:52.507 --> 00:30:55.342
Ah, you're good... Good boy, Tom.

438
00:30:55.510 --> 00:30:56.844
Yeah.

439
00:30:59.306 --> 00:31:03.684
I'll tell you something, son. If you don't
follow through on your dreams...

440
00:31:03.852 --> 00:31:05.372
you might as well be a vegetable.

441
00:31:06.938 --> 00:31:08.897
What type of vegetable?

442
00:31:09.065 --> 00:31:12.818
I don't know. A cabbage.

443
00:31:12.986 --> 00:31:14.862
Yeah. A cabbage.

444
00:31:17.616 --> 00:31:19.325
Here you are. Don't lose it, will you?

445
00:31:19.492 --> 00:31:23.245
- Promise I'll look after it.
- Right.

446
00:31:23.413 --> 00:31:26.999
So keep an eye on the place for me,
won't you, Tom?

447
00:31:27.167 --> 00:31:30.044
And...

448
00:31:30.211 --> 00:31:32.880
- don't forget to feed the fowls.
- That's my job.

449
00:31:33.048 --> 00:31:36.592
Yeah, and, you know, you can
give the eggs to Mom.

450
00:31:36.760 --> 00:31:39.136
And what else is there?

451
00:31:39.304 --> 00:31:41.847
Uh... Oh, yes.

452
00:31:42.015 --> 00:31:45.893
You can pee on my lemon tree
for me, if you like, while I'm away.

453
00:31:46.061 --> 00:31:49.313
And... Well, there's nothing wrong
in peeing on your lemon tree.

454
00:31:49.481 --> 00:31:53.275
As Confucius used to say, it's the best
natural fertilizer in the world, you know?

455
00:31:53.443 --> 00:31:54.443
Who's Confucius?

456
00:31:54.611 --> 00:31:56.403
Oh, he's a bloke who lives up in Duneaton.

457
00:31:56.571 --> 00:31:57.931
Well, thanks for your help, chaps.

458
00:31:58.073 --> 00:31:59.907
- Good luck, Burt.
- Thanks, Jeff.

459
00:32:00.075 --> 00:32:02.409
- You show them.
- I will.

460
00:32:02.577 --> 00:32:04.737
- Take it easy, Burt.
- That's not one of the things...

461
00:32:04.829 --> 00:32:06.269
I'm planning on doing, George.

462
00:32:06.373 --> 00:32:08.916
- Cheerio, love.
- Good luck.

463
00:32:09.084 --> 00:32:10.751
Cheerio, my friend.

464
00:32:10.919 --> 00:32:13.453
If you don't go when you wanna go,
when you do go, you'll find you've gone.

465
00:32:13.463 --> 00:32:14.963
- I'll see you.
- See you, Burt.

466
00:32:15.131 --> 00:32:16.965
Bye, Burt.

467
00:32:17.133 --> 00:32:19.134
- Good luck!
- Cheerio!

468
00:32:19.302 --> 00:32:20.552
See you, Burt!

469
00:32:34.025 --> 00:32:35.067
Look at that.

470
00:32:45.286 --> 00:32:46.787
Well, Fran...

471
00:32:46.955 --> 00:32:49.289
I'm finally on my way.

472
00:32:51.793 --> 00:32:56.004
You know, I thought some more
of the blokes from the club...

473
00:32:56.172 --> 00:32:58.132
would have dropped by to see me off.

474
00:32:58.299 --> 00:33:00.801
Well, they probably had to work today.

475
00:33:00.969 --> 00:33:03.220
Yeah. Yeah, that's right.

476
00:33:03.388 --> 00:33:07.141
You know, young Tom tells me...

477
00:33:07.308 --> 00:33:09.143
no one thinks I can do it.

478
00:33:09.310 --> 00:33:11.270
Do you think I can do it, Fran?

479
00:33:11.438 --> 00:33:12.938
Oh, I don't know, Burt.

480
00:33:13.106 --> 00:33:15.232
I don't think it really matters
one way or the other.

481
00:33:15.775 --> 00:33:17.234
Yeah.

482
00:33:21.489 --> 00:33:25.200
You know, I read something once,
years ago...

483
00:33:25.368 --> 00:33:28.746
and I learned it off by heart. It was...

484
00:33:28.913 --> 00:33:32.708
Theodore Roosevelt said it.
He said it's...

485
00:33:32.876 --> 00:33:36.962
He said it's not the critic that counts...

486
00:33:37.130 --> 00:33:41.216
not the man who points out
how the strong man stumbles...

487
00:33:41.384 --> 00:33:46.722
or where the doer of deeds
could have done them better...

488
00:33:46.890 --> 00:33:48.307
you know...

489
00:33:48.475 --> 00:33:53.854
the credit belongs to the man
who is actually in the arena.

490
00:34:01.696 --> 00:34:04.615
- Wind your window down. Down!
- What?

491
00:34:05.825 --> 00:34:08.202
- Some beer money.
- What?

492
00:34:08.369 --> 00:34:10.204
Some beer money.

493
00:34:10.371 --> 00:34:12.664
I don't drink.

494
00:34:12.832 --> 00:34:16.168
- And good luck! You go well.
- Thanks, mate.

495
00:34:16.336 --> 00:34:17.544
Show them Kiwis can fly, huh?

496
00:34:17.712 --> 00:34:19.838
Yeah. I'll bring you back
the Statue of Liberty.

497
00:34:21.382 --> 00:34:22.883
Good on you, mate. Thanks a lot.

498
00:34:41.361 --> 00:34:42.903
Hey, not so fast!

499
00:34:45.406 --> 00:34:47.074
Crikey!

500
00:34:48.117 --> 00:34:50.410
Take it easy, mate!

501
00:34:52.330 --> 00:34:54.081
I thought it was a goner.

502
00:34:57.210 --> 00:34:59.127
Whoa! Whoa!

503
00:35:01.256 --> 00:35:04.007
- Better get going.
- Yeah. All right.

504
00:35:04.175 --> 00:35:08.470
Take care of the old jalopy, won't you?

505
00:35:08.638 --> 00:35:10.389
- You look after yourself.
- Yeah, I will.

506
00:35:10.557 --> 00:35:13.433
- You've got your pills and everything, right?
- Yeah, right as rain.

507
00:35:13.601 --> 00:35:15.394
Okay.

508
00:35:15.562 --> 00:35:17.312
All right.

509
00:35:18.648 --> 00:35:20.232
You come back in one piece.

510
00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:22.734
I will. Cheerio.

511
00:35:31.077 --> 00:35:34.538
- Ah. Where's the captain?
- Down below.

512
00:35:34.706 --> 00:35:36.748
- Down that gangway there.
- Thanks.

513
00:35:37.876 --> 00:35:39.501
Here.

514
00:35:39.669 --> 00:35:42.045
I'm looking for the captain.

515
00:35:42.213 --> 00:35:44.631
- That's me.
- Oh.

516
00:35:44.799 --> 00:35:47.426
Well, my name is Burt Munro.

517
00:35:49.012 --> 00:35:53.098
I'm supposed to do a job
to work my passage to Los Angeles.

518
00:35:53.266 --> 00:35:54.641
Yeah, well, I hope you can cook.

519
00:35:54.809 --> 00:35:56.310
Cook?

520
00:35:57.103 --> 00:35:59.104
Well, I'll give it a go.

521
00:35:59.272 --> 00:36:00.939
There's the galley.

522
00:36:02.358 --> 00:36:05.569
Oh. Crikey.

523
00:36:07.113 --> 00:36:08.572
Who does the dishes, mate?

524
00:36:08.740 --> 00:36:10.657
You.

525
00:36:15.622 --> 00:36:16.997
Mm. Smells good!

526
00:36:17.165 --> 00:36:18.790
What do you have for us today, Burt?

527
00:36:18.958 --> 00:36:21.126
That's good Kiwi tucker.

528
00:36:23.338 --> 00:36:26.173
Don't let Burt see you doing that.

529
00:36:26.341 --> 00:36:29.426
Here, don't spoil it with all that sauce.

530
00:36:29.594 --> 00:36:31.470
- Sorry, Burt.
- Stand the crowds!

531
00:36:36.643 --> 00:36:38.894
- Watch the movie, Burt?
- What's that?

532
00:36:39.062 --> 00:36:40.520
Are you gonna watch the movie?

533
00:36:40.688 --> 00:36:42.522
Yeah. What's it called?

534
00:36:42.690 --> 00:36:44.358
Broken Barrier.

535
00:36:44.525 --> 00:36:46.985
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah. It's supposed to be good.

536
00:36:47.153 --> 00:36:49.237
Is Jane Russell in it?

537
00:36:49.405 --> 00:36:51.907
- Space for you over here, Burt.
- Yeah.

538
00:36:52.075 --> 00:36:53.575
Whoa!

539
00:36:53.743 --> 00:36:54.868
Move your legs.

540
00:36:55.036 --> 00:36:58.997
All right. Okay.

541
00:36:59.165 --> 00:37:02.042
- Smoke?
- No. Not for me, mate.

542
00:37:02.210 --> 00:37:03.877
- You don't smoke, Burt?
- No, I don't.

543
00:37:04.045 --> 00:37:05.545
And that's why people say to me:

544
00:37:05.713 --> 00:37:07.422
"How do you keep going
at your age, Burt?"

545
00:37:07.590 --> 00:37:09.341
And I say,
"Well, because I don't smoke."

546
00:37:09.509 --> 00:37:12.511
And that's what I'm telling
you young monkeys. Don't smoke.

547
00:37:12.679 --> 00:37:15.389
- Ha, ha, ha.
- You can laugh, but my dad said:

548
00:37:15.556 --> 00:37:17.891
"Why contaminate your lungs
with tobacco smoke?

549
00:37:18.059 --> 00:37:19.979
The only thing you accomplish
by the smoking...

550
00:37:20.061 --> 00:37:22.301
is destroying your lungs
and shortening your life."

551
00:37:22.438 --> 00:37:23.981
Kill the lights!

552
00:37:27.568 --> 00:37:28.986
Is Jane Russell in this?

553
00:37:30.071 --> 00:37:31.238
Done well, Burt.

554
00:37:31.406 --> 00:37:33.824
Yeah. Thanks, mate.

555
00:37:33.992 --> 00:37:35.659
- All the best.
- Heh.

556
00:37:41.416 --> 00:37:43.083
- Good luck to you, Burt.
- Thanks.

557
00:37:43.251 --> 00:37:45.293
Remember what I said.
Don't smoke.

558
00:37:46.004 --> 00:37:49.256
- I'm trying.
- Cheerio, mates. See you.

559
00:37:50.341 --> 00:37:53.176
Welcome to the United States.
Customs to the left.

560
00:37:53.344 --> 00:37:54.761
Thank you. Good to be here.

561
00:37:54.929 --> 00:38:02.929
Good day.

562
00:38:03.604 --> 00:38:06.044
Please stand behind the yellow line
until you are called, sir.

563
00:38:06.190 --> 00:38:08.567
- What's that?
- Behind the yellow line.

564
00:38:08.735 --> 00:38:11.278
The yellow line. Oh, yeah.

565
00:38:20.038 --> 00:38:21.079
Good day.

566
00:38:21.247 --> 00:38:22.914
Passport and customs declaration, please.

567
00:38:23.082 --> 00:38:25.751
Right. Here you are.

568
00:38:31.758 --> 00:38:33.958
And how long do you intend
to stay in the United States?

569
00:38:34.093 --> 00:38:38.221
However long it takes me
to get to Bonneville and back.

570
00:38:38.389 --> 00:38:39.598
And the purpose of your visit?

571
00:38:39.766 --> 00:38:43.977
To set a land-speed record on my Indian.

572
00:38:44.145 --> 00:38:45.812
Hm. Indian.

573
00:38:45.980 --> 00:38:48.857
Mr. Munro,
this is your first time to America.

574
00:38:49.025 --> 00:38:50.442
Yes, sir.

575
00:38:50.610 --> 00:38:52.650
You gave some rather odd answers
to the officer...

576
00:38:52.695 --> 00:38:54.935
so we have a few further questions
we'd like to ask.

577
00:38:54.989 --> 00:38:56.239
Well, fire away.

578
00:38:56.407 --> 00:38:58.658
Let's go over again what you said.

579
00:38:58.826 --> 00:39:01.369
Now, what exactly do you intend to do
here in the United States?

580
00:39:01.537 --> 00:39:03.580
Well, set a land-speed record.

581
00:39:03.748 --> 00:39:06.500
Uh-huh. And how do you
intend to do that, sir?

582
00:39:06.667 --> 00:39:10.420
On my motorcycle. It's in the hold
of the ship at the moment...

583
00:39:10.588 --> 00:39:13.131
and they're gonna unload it tomorrow.

584
00:39:13.299 --> 00:39:16.510
It's an Indian, a 1920 Indian Scout...

585
00:39:16.677 --> 00:39:19.471
modified somewhat.

586
00:39:19.639 --> 00:39:22.557
You know what?
I think I've read about your bike.

587
00:39:22.725 --> 00:39:23.767
Oh, yeah?

588
00:39:23.935 --> 00:39:26.603
It was in Popular Mechanics
a couple of years ago.

589
00:39:26.771 --> 00:39:28.021
That's right. That's me.

590
00:39:28.189 --> 00:39:32.192
Yes. Leslie Hobbs from Christchurch
sent that story.

591
00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:35.237
What was it?
"Fastest motorcycle in Australia."

592
00:39:35.404 --> 00:39:37.739
Yeah, and in New Zealand.

593
00:39:39.408 --> 00:39:41.451
Well, I guess you're legitimate,
Mr. Munro.

594
00:39:41.619 --> 00:39:44.371
It sounds like we should be very honored
to have you here in America.

595
00:39:44.539 --> 00:39:46.331
- Thank you.
- Here's what I'm gonna do.

596
00:39:46.499 --> 00:39:50.252
I'm gonna give you 6 months. That should
be time enough to get the job done.

597
00:39:51.712 --> 00:39:54.089
- Welcome to the U.S.A.
- Thank you very much.

598
00:39:54.257 --> 00:39:57.384
- Good luck, sir.
- Thank you.

599
00:40:02.974 --> 00:40:04.349
Gear's in the trunk.

600
00:40:04.517 --> 00:40:06.101
- What?
- Bags in the back.

601
00:40:06.269 --> 00:40:08.228
Bag, back.

602
00:40:08.396 --> 00:40:11.231
Don't worry about me.
I'll do it myself.

603
00:40:11.399 --> 00:40:12.941
It's good.

604
00:40:25.371 --> 00:40:28.707
- All right.
- Sit in the back. In the back.

605
00:40:28.875 --> 00:40:30.584
- Huh?
- You, in the back.

606
00:40:30.751 --> 00:40:34.045
Oh. I'll tell you something, mate.

607
00:40:34.213 --> 00:40:37.257
I don't want to get old around here.
Ha, ha.

608
00:40:37.425 --> 00:40:39.885
Ah. Toorah.

609
00:40:43.222 --> 00:40:44.431
- Where to?
- What?

610
00:40:44.599 --> 00:40:45.849
Where to?

611
00:40:46.017 --> 00:40:48.518
Hollywood. I want to go to Hollywood.

612
00:40:48.686 --> 00:40:50.937
I want to see the film stars.

613
00:40:51.105 --> 00:40:53.440
Okay. We go to Hollywood.

614
00:40:53.608 --> 00:40:55.650
Where in Hollywood?

615
00:40:55.985 --> 00:40:59.654
A motel on Sunset Boulevard.

616
00:40:59.822 --> 00:41:01.698
I hear that's a pretty great street.

617
00:41:01.866 --> 00:41:03.950
I don't know who you talking to lately.

618
00:41:04.118 --> 00:41:07.037
- Which motel?
- Recommend one.

619
00:41:07.205 --> 00:41:10.123
Come, now. What do you think I am,
an encyclopedia?

620
00:41:11.125 --> 00:41:14.544
Drop me somewhere
and I'll sort it out myself.

621
00:41:22.428 --> 00:41:25.096
They must have a big electricity bill here.

622
00:41:29.435 --> 00:41:32.896
Firestone, Shell...

623
00:41:34.482 --> 00:41:38.485
It's all about cars, isn't it?
I've never seen so many cars.

624
00:41:38.653 --> 00:41:42.322
- You say something, man?
- I said, I've never seen so many cars.

625
00:41:42.490 --> 00:41:46.117
- Gotta get around somehow.
- Yeah.

626
00:41:49.956 --> 00:41:51.998
Oh, look. There's a bowling alley.

627
00:41:52.166 --> 00:41:53.667
Do you bowl?

628
00:41:59.465 --> 00:42:01.633
What's he honking his horn about?

629
00:42:04.929 --> 00:42:07.514
Jeez! Crikey! Did you see that?

630
00:42:07.682 --> 00:42:10.892
Don't think... He's just got...

631
00:42:11.060 --> 00:42:13.144
He's crazy! He's nuts!

632
00:42:13.312 --> 00:42:15.146
He did it again.

633
00:42:15.314 --> 00:42:18.400
Don't stare. There's a lot
of crazy people in this town.

634
00:42:18.567 --> 00:42:20.777
I've never seen anything like that before.

635
00:42:31.872 --> 00:42:33.873
- This should do.
- What's the damage?

636
00:42:34.041 --> 00:42:37.377
Twenty-eight dollars plus bag, $29.

637
00:42:37.545 --> 00:42:42.382
What? Did you just say
what I thought you said?

638
00:42:42.550 --> 00:42:43.591
Are you deaf?

639
00:42:43.759 --> 00:42:45.719
- What?
- Are you deaf?

640
00:42:45.886 --> 00:42:49.723
Yeah, I am a bit deaf, but I'm not stupid.
How much did you say it was?

641
00:42:49.890 --> 00:42:51.224
Twenty-nine dollar.

642
00:42:51.392 --> 00:42:53.101
No. I don't want to
buy the cab, mate.

643
00:42:53.269 --> 00:42:55.854
I just want to pay the fare, that's all.

644
00:42:56.022 --> 00:42:57.355
- Where are you from?
- What?

645
00:42:57.523 --> 00:42:59.899
- You are British?
- No. You must be joking.

646
00:43:00.067 --> 00:43:03.570
I'm no pommie. I'm from New Zealand.

647
00:43:03.738 --> 00:43:05.780
- Well, this is America.
- Yeah?

648
00:43:05.948 --> 00:43:08.700
And the fare is right there
on the meter. Twenty-nine dollar.

649
00:43:08.868 --> 00:43:11.911
- Yeah.
- Open your wallet and let the moths out.

650
00:43:12.079 --> 00:43:16.041
Yeah, I'm doing it. I'm doing it.
Here you go, $29.

651
00:43:16.709 --> 00:43:17.917
Hold on. Don't forget the tip.

652
00:43:18.085 --> 00:43:20.712
- What?
- Yes. We tip in America.

653
00:43:20.880 --> 00:43:22.172
- Oh, yeah?
- Ten percent.

654
00:43:22.340 --> 00:43:24.424
- How much?
- Ten percent.

655
00:43:24.592 --> 00:43:27.844
Oh, yeah. There you are. Ten cents.

656
00:43:36.103 --> 00:43:37.979
- Excuse me, sir.
- Yeah?

657
00:43:38.147 --> 00:43:39.939
- You look like a generous man.
- What?

658
00:43:40.107 --> 00:43:41.358
You look like a generous man.

659
00:43:41.525 --> 00:43:43.443
- Oh, do I?
- Yes, you do.

660
00:43:43.611 --> 00:43:45.945
Would you like to buy a flower
to give to someone special?

661
00:43:46.113 --> 00:43:47.572
No, I'm sorry.
I don't have any cash.

662
00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:50.825
Oh, don't worry.
The money goes to a good cause.

663
00:43:50.993 --> 00:43:52.913
It's for an organization
that helps needy people.

664
00:43:53.079 --> 00:43:56.956
- All right. Well, how much is it?
- Just give what you can afford.

665
00:43:57.124 --> 00:44:01.169
All right. Well, they all look
the same to me.

666
00:44:01.337 --> 00:44:03.963
- They're all green.
- Yes, that's why we call them greenbacks.

667
00:44:04.131 --> 00:44:06.051
- This looks like a one.
- Oh, look, there's one.

668
00:44:06.133 --> 00:44:07.926
Thanks. You have a good day.

669
00:44:08.094 --> 00:44:10.470
Hey, come on, miss.
That's a 10.

670
00:44:10.638 --> 00:44:12.263
I didn't want to pay that much.

671
00:44:12.431 --> 00:44:13.973
Hey, come back!

672
00:44:17.103 --> 00:44:18.311
Crikey.

673
00:44:18.479 --> 00:44:20.313
- Hey, baby.
- What do you want?

674
00:44:20.481 --> 00:44:22.315
- You want to go?
- Go where?

675
00:44:22.483 --> 00:44:23.858
Go inside.

676
00:44:24.026 --> 00:44:25.568
I'm going inside.

677
00:44:25.736 --> 00:44:27.529
I'll take you around the world.

678
00:44:27.696 --> 00:44:29.823
I've just come from halfway
around the world.

679
00:44:29.990 --> 00:44:31.908
- Fifteen bucks, baby.
- What?

680
00:44:32.076 --> 00:44:36.287
- Fifteen bucks.
- No. It's all right. Go away.

681
00:44:41.752 --> 00:44:43.753
Hello.

682
00:44:46.882 --> 00:44:49.134
Phew. Well, I need a room.

683
00:44:49.301 --> 00:44:51.344
A room will cost you 5 bucks an hour.

684
00:44:51.512 --> 00:44:54.013
Well, I'm planning on staying
a bit longer than that.

685
00:44:54.181 --> 00:44:56.391
- How long?
- I don't know. A couple of days, I guess.

686
00:44:56.559 --> 00:44:58.726
- Double occupancy?
- What?

687
00:44:58.894 --> 00:45:00.353
Double occupancy?

688
00:45:00.521 --> 00:45:03.231
No. Just me, myself and I.

689
00:45:03.399 --> 00:45:07.152
Will it cost a lot?
Because I can't afford a lot.

690
00:45:07.945 --> 00:45:10.363
- Are you a member of AAA?
- What?

691
00:45:10.531 --> 00:45:12.782
- Are you a AAA member?
- Never heard of them.

692
00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:14.033
Never heard of AAA?

693
00:45:14.201 --> 00:45:19.205
No, Miss Brittlebritches,
I have not heard of AAA.

694
00:45:19.373 --> 00:45:21.207
Okay, let's just say
you are a member, doll.

695
00:45:21.375 --> 00:45:23.668
- All right.
- That'll save you 10 percent.

696
00:45:23.836 --> 00:45:26.546
- Oh.
- How does 22 bucks a night sound?

697
00:45:26.714 --> 00:45:29.424
That much? Is that cheap?

698
00:45:29.592 --> 00:45:31.926
Honey, that's cheaper than cheap.

699
00:45:32.094 --> 00:45:34.554
Oh, good. Yeah.

700
00:45:34.722 --> 00:45:37.557
- What's your name?
- Tina Washington.

701
00:45:37.725 --> 00:45:40.393
Well, Tina Washington,
I want you to have this.

702
00:45:40.561 --> 00:45:44.230
It might cheer you up a bit,
get some of that muck off your pluck.

703
00:45:44.398 --> 00:45:49.027
Well, thank you. That's the first nice thing
that's happened around here all week.

704
00:45:49.195 --> 00:45:50.528
Well, you're welcome.

705
00:45:50.696 --> 00:45:54.782
My name's Burt Munro, from New Zealand.
I'm from down under.

706
00:45:54.950 --> 00:45:57.911
Well, hello, Burt Munro
from New Zealand down under.

707
00:45:58.078 --> 00:46:00.288
I tell you, I've had a heck of a night.

708
00:46:00.456 --> 00:46:02.707
Welcome to Hollyweird.

709
00:46:54.009 --> 00:46:55.802
Hello.

710
00:46:55.970 --> 00:46:57.470
Anybody home?

711
00:46:59.473 --> 00:47:01.516
- Hello, Tina.
- Good morning, Burt.

712
00:47:01.684 --> 00:47:04.394
- You still here? Oh.
- Mm-hm.

713
00:47:04.562 --> 00:47:07.146
Well, that's why you were
so crabby last night.

714
00:47:07.314 --> 00:47:10.608
- Don't you ever get any sleep?
- Honey, I work the night shift.

715
00:47:10.776 --> 00:47:13.486
I'm out of here as soon
as James turns up. And he's late.

716
00:47:13.654 --> 00:47:17.198
Oh. Yeah. Could you phone
this number for me?

717
00:47:17.866 --> 00:47:20.785
It's a shipping company
and they've got a big box of mine...

718
00:47:20.953 --> 00:47:25.456
and I want to know how
can I arrange to get it?

719
00:47:26.834 --> 00:47:28.794
No, you talk to them.
They'll never get my accent.

720
00:47:28.919 --> 00:47:30.503
Okay. What do you
want me to ask them?

721
00:47:30.671 --> 00:47:32.130
One moment, please.

722
00:47:32.298 --> 00:47:36.593
Ask them when will Burt Munro's box
containing the motorcycle...

723
00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:38.469
be ready for pickup?

724
00:47:38.637 --> 00:47:41.306
- Hello. I'm calling for Mr. Burt Munro.
- Munro?

725
00:47:41.473 --> 00:47:44.073
Yes. He'd like to know when
the box containing his motorcycle...

726
00:47:44.143 --> 00:47:46.686
- will be available for pickup.
- What ship?

727
00:47:46.854 --> 00:47:49.439
- What ship?
- The Rangatira from New Zealand.

728
00:47:49.607 --> 00:47:51.524
The Rangatira from New Zealand.

729
00:47:51.692 --> 00:47:53.651
- It's arrived.
- So he can claim it?

730
00:47:53.819 --> 00:47:58.031
Tomorrow from the Long Beach
Customs Holding Area.

731
00:47:58.198 --> 00:48:01.576
- Okay, thank you. I'll tell him. Bye-bye.
- That was pretty fast.

732
00:48:01.744 --> 00:48:03.703
You're late!

733
00:48:05.664 --> 00:48:08.041
I can't stand another minute in this place.

734
00:48:08.208 --> 00:48:09.834
Let me buy you breakfast.

735
00:48:12.546 --> 00:48:14.213
This is great.

736
00:48:14.381 --> 00:48:18.551
I've never seen a menu
with photographs before.

737
00:48:18.719 --> 00:48:20.219
Ready to order, sir?

738
00:48:20.387 --> 00:48:22.221
- What?
- Are you ready?

739
00:48:22.389 --> 00:48:27.393
Oh, yes. I think the Double Delight.

740
00:48:27.561 --> 00:48:28.561
That's for me.

741
00:48:28.729 --> 00:48:30.730
- How would you like your eggs?
- What?

742
00:48:30.898 --> 00:48:34.776
- How would you like your eggs?
- Well, I'd like them cooked.

743
00:48:34.943 --> 00:48:38.571
Sunny-side up? Over easy?

744
00:48:38.739 --> 00:48:40.448
I don't know.
Whatever you recommend.

745
00:48:40.616 --> 00:48:42.033
Over easy is best.

746
00:48:42.201 --> 00:48:44.035
All right. Eggs over easy.

747
00:48:44.203 --> 00:48:45.244
Make that two.

748
00:48:46.038 --> 00:48:48.456
Over easy. I must remember that.

749
00:48:48.624 --> 00:48:51.959
Well, I like this American breakfast thing.

750
00:48:52.127 --> 00:48:54.754
It's good.

751
00:48:54.922 --> 00:48:59.217
So, my girl, where's the best place
for me to get a used car?

752
00:48:59.385 --> 00:49:01.427
- The valley.
- Oh, yeah?

753
00:49:01.595 --> 00:49:03.195
After breakfast, I could take you there.

754
00:49:03.305 --> 00:49:04.847
Oh, well, thank you.

755
00:49:06.058 --> 00:49:07.517
And I'm not a girl.

756
00:49:10.396 --> 00:49:12.605
I'm a boy.

757
00:49:12.773 --> 00:49:14.440
Oh.

758
00:49:15.150 --> 00:49:18.444
Well, I thought there was something
a little odd about you.

759
00:49:18.612 --> 00:49:22.031
But you're still a sweetheart.

760
00:49:24.702 --> 00:49:26.119
Yeah.

761
00:49:39.299 --> 00:49:41.426
Well, thanks a million, Tina.

762
00:49:41.593 --> 00:49:43.803
There are stacks of cars here.

763
00:49:43.971 --> 00:49:47.181
- I'll be back at the motel later on.
- Bye.

764
00:49:47.349 --> 00:49:48.850
All right, love.

765
00:49:53.939 --> 00:49:55.982
- Hello.
- How may I help you, sir?

766
00:49:56.150 --> 00:50:00.403
Yeah. I want to buy a car. A cheap car.
A very cheap car.

767
00:50:00.571 --> 00:50:02.655
Well, you've come to
the right place, amigo.

768
00:50:02.823 --> 00:50:07.243
In fact, if you can find cars like these
any cheaper, they're probably stolen.

769
00:50:07.411 --> 00:50:10.204
My name is Burt.
Burt Munro from New Zealand.

770
00:50:10.372 --> 00:50:12.457
- Nice to meet you.
- I'm Fernando from El Salvador.

771
00:50:12.624 --> 00:50:14.959
- Nice to meet you, Mr. Munro.
- You can call me Burt.

772
00:50:15.127 --> 00:50:17.336
- Okay, Mr. Burt.
- Yeah.

773
00:50:17.504 --> 00:50:20.131
So how much were you looking
to spend here, Mr. Burt?

774
00:50:20.299 --> 00:50:21.591
Not a lot, Fernando.

775
00:50:21.759 --> 00:50:24.510
I haven't got much left after
the cab ride I took yesterday.

776
00:50:25.846 --> 00:50:27.764
You want 399 for this?

777
00:50:27.931 --> 00:50:30.224
Sounds a bit sick.

778
00:50:30.392 --> 00:50:31.934
Well, what would you offer me?

779
00:50:32.102 --> 00:50:36.022
Listen, I'll give you 200
if you do me a favor.

780
00:50:36.190 --> 00:50:38.524
Throw in the use of your workshop...

781
00:50:38.692 --> 00:50:41.861
and some of that junk I see lying around...

782
00:50:42.029 --> 00:50:47.116
because I've got to knock up a trailer
to drag my bike over to Bonneville.

783
00:50:47.284 --> 00:50:49.535
That's not a favor.
Three twenty-five is a favor.

784
00:50:49.703 --> 00:50:52.497
No, 225.

785
00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:56.375
You're a tough customer, Mr. Burt,
but I like you.

786
00:50:56.543 --> 00:50:58.169
I'm gonna give it to you for 250...

787
00:50:58.337 --> 00:51:00.880
and you can use the workshop,
but only at night.

788
00:51:01.048 --> 00:51:02.548
All right. What about tonight?

789
00:51:02.716 --> 00:51:04.217
Yeah, yeah. Yeah, tonight's okay.

790
00:51:04.384 --> 00:51:06.344
All right. Let's stop the car.

791
00:51:06.512 --> 00:51:08.846
Let's get this thing running properly.

792
00:51:22.402 --> 00:51:25.404
There. That sounds better.

793
00:51:25.572 --> 00:51:26.572
Let me drive.

794
00:51:26.740 --> 00:51:28.491
Okay. Come on.

795
00:51:28.659 --> 00:51:31.869
Yeah, she's singing like a bird now.

796
00:51:32.037 --> 00:51:33.746
She's a good old girl, isn't she?

797
00:51:33.914 --> 00:51:35.456
Here we are. All right.

798
00:51:42.089 --> 00:51:44.257
You make a left here, Mr. Burt.

799
00:51:44.424 --> 00:51:45.925
All right.

800
00:51:49.763 --> 00:51:52.765
- Crikey!
- You're on the wrong... Stop the car!

801
00:51:52.933 --> 00:51:55.476
Stop the... Aah!

802
00:51:55.644 --> 00:51:57.436
Turn! Turn this way!

803
00:51:58.522 --> 00:52:00.106
Stop the car!

804
00:52:02.276 --> 00:52:04.443
Hey, keep your shirt on.

805
00:52:05.863 --> 00:52:07.613
Scoot over, you stupid old bastard.

806
00:52:07.781 --> 00:52:09.282
Thought I was back in New Zealand.

807
00:52:09.449 --> 00:52:11.784
We drive on the other side
of the road over there.

808
00:52:11.952 --> 00:52:15.788
- Yeah? Gonna get us all killed.
- Yeah.

809
00:52:15.956 --> 00:52:17.832
Well, you're not in New Zealand.

810
00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:19.876
- You're in America.
- Yeah, I know.

811
00:52:20.043 --> 00:52:22.795
- We drive on the right side of the road.
- Yeah.

812
00:52:30.095 --> 00:52:33.306
- Whoa.
- Now, Burt, let me give you some advice.

813
00:52:33.473 --> 00:52:35.016
What?

814
00:52:36.476 --> 00:52:38.811
When you're driving,
not only here in America...

815
00:52:38.979 --> 00:52:41.397
- but anywheres around the world...
- Yeah?

816
00:52:41.565 --> 00:52:44.150
the driver should always be
in the center of the road.

817
00:52:44.318 --> 00:52:46.819
- Right.
- In the center. If you're not in the center...

818
00:52:46.987 --> 00:52:49.530
you're on the wrong side
of the road. Okay?

819
00:52:49.698 --> 00:52:50.740
Yep.

820
00:52:58.749 --> 00:53:01.125
Well, you want this right here?

821
00:53:01.293 --> 00:53:03.044
Yeah.

822
00:53:05.255 --> 00:53:08.049
That's it. Yeah, good.

823
00:53:08.216 --> 00:53:09.759
Got it.

824
00:53:09.927 --> 00:53:11.802
Dios mio, it's 3 a. m. in the morning.

825
00:53:11.970 --> 00:53:14.388
Yeah, well, time flies when
you're having fun, doesn't it?

826
00:53:16.016 --> 00:53:18.643
You know, when I told you you could
use the workshop at night...

827
00:53:18.810 --> 00:53:21.604
I didn't mean all night.
My wife's gonna kill me.

828
00:53:21.772 --> 00:53:23.064
You take yourself back home...

829
00:53:23.231 --> 00:53:25.390
and I'll have a snooze
in the back of the car...

830
00:53:25.400 --> 00:53:29.195
and I'll lock up the place
before I go to sleep.

831
00:53:29.363 --> 00:53:33.032
Seems to me like a whole lot of effort
to sell a lousy $250 motorcar.

832
00:53:33.200 --> 00:53:34.450
- Yeah.
- Okay, Mr. Burt.

833
00:53:34.618 --> 00:53:36.494
Pull the door down.
Have a good night.

834
00:53:37.412 --> 00:53:40.581
Hey, Fernando, where do I go to...?

835
00:53:40.749 --> 00:53:42.708
Where do I take a leak around here?

836
00:53:42.876 --> 00:53:43.960
A leak?

837
00:53:44.127 --> 00:53:47.088
Yeah. A pee. Trouble with
the old prostate, you know.

838
00:53:47.255 --> 00:53:50.883
Yeah. Go straight through those doors.
There's a door there that says "cabaliero."

839
00:53:51.051 --> 00:53:52.426
- All right.
- Okay.

840
00:53:52.594 --> 00:53:55.054
I'll see you in the morning, early, okay?

841
00:53:55.222 --> 00:53:56.847
Good night.

842
00:53:57.015 --> 00:53:58.057
Now, where were we?

843
00:54:02.145 --> 00:54:04.855
- Burt?
- Huh?

844
00:54:05.023 --> 00:54:08.401
- Buenos dias, Mr. Burt.
- Oh. All right.

845
00:54:09.820 --> 00:54:11.237
So did you get it all finished?

846
00:54:11.405 --> 00:54:15.074
Yeah. All I need to do is find
a couple of wheels...

847
00:54:15.242 --> 00:54:16.784
and I'll be ready to roll.

848
00:54:16.952 --> 00:54:19.472
Hey, you know, I got some wheels
in the back you could have...

849
00:54:19.579 --> 00:54:22.164
- if you just do me a favor.
- Say the word.

850
00:54:25.585 --> 00:54:26.961
Crank it now, Fernando.

851
00:54:28.296 --> 00:54:30.297
Good.

852
00:54:30.465 --> 00:54:32.174
- Burt.
- Yeah?

853
00:54:32.342 --> 00:54:33.634
You're a goddamn genius.

854
00:54:33.802 --> 00:54:36.929
- Thank you.
- Hey, listen, why you gotta go?

855
00:54:37.097 --> 00:54:38.764
Stick around a while. I'll pay you well.

856
00:54:38.932 --> 00:54:41.392
Sorry, mate. I've got to get
to Bonneville by the 23rd.

857
00:54:41.560 --> 00:54:44.937
That's when Speed Week starts,
and, you know, I've gotta hit the road.

858
00:54:45.105 --> 00:54:46.981
Well, you always got a job here.

859
00:54:47.149 --> 00:54:48.983
Thanks, mate. I'll see you.

860
00:54:49.151 --> 00:54:51.736
- Best of luck to you.
- Ta-ta.

861
00:55:05.125 --> 00:55:06.250
Hello, love.

862
00:55:06.418 --> 00:55:08.794
- I was worried about you.
- Oh, yeah?

863
00:55:08.962 --> 00:55:11.255
Housekeeping said you didn't
sleep in your bed all night.

864
00:55:11.423 --> 00:55:13.591
Oh. Well, do I get a discount for that?

865
00:55:14.134 --> 00:55:15.134
I doubt it.

866
00:55:15.302 --> 00:55:17.928
Now, I need you to show me on a map
how to get to Long Beach.

867
00:55:18.096 --> 00:55:21.098
- I've got to pick up my bike today.
- I'm finished here in 15 minutes.

868
00:55:21.266 --> 00:55:22.308
I'll come with you.

869
00:55:25.353 --> 00:55:28.689
Not a bad set of wheels for 250 bucks, eh?

870
00:55:28.857 --> 00:55:30.274
You sure it'll make it to Utah?

871
00:55:30.442 --> 00:55:34.528
Yeah. This old girl'd get
to New Zealand and back.

872
00:55:34.696 --> 00:55:36.030
Here.

873
00:55:36.198 --> 00:55:38.282
- Hop in, my fair lady.
- Thank you.

874
00:55:40.577 --> 00:55:43.120
The bloke who sold me this car,
he gave me a good tip.

875
00:55:43.288 --> 00:55:46.499
He said, always remember that
the driver... That's me.

876
00:55:46.666 --> 00:55:50.252
- should be on the center of the road.
- Look out!

877
00:55:50.420 --> 00:55:53.672
Yeah, all right. In New Zealand,
we always drive on the other side.

878
00:55:56.510 --> 00:55:58.219
- You do?
- Yeah. Sorry about that.

879
00:55:59.763 --> 00:56:01.643
- Do you want me to drive?
- No. It's all right.

880
00:56:01.807 --> 00:56:03.724
I've got to get used to it, don't I?

881
00:56:06.019 --> 00:56:08.062
This should be Customs right here.

882
00:56:08.230 --> 00:56:09.522
Right.

883
00:56:15.946 --> 00:56:17.696
- Hello.
- May I help you, sir?

884
00:56:17.864 --> 00:56:19.573
Yeah. My name's Burt Munro...

885
00:56:19.741 --> 00:56:21.992
and I've come to pick up my motorcycle.

886
00:56:22.160 --> 00:56:24.203
I came into port two days ago
from New Zealand...

887
00:56:24.371 --> 00:56:27.832
and, uh...
On a freighter called Rangatira...

888
00:56:27.999 --> 00:56:30.399
and I was told to come here
to clear it through Customs.

889
00:56:30.502 --> 00:56:32.253
Okay. Mr. Munro.

890
00:56:32.420 --> 00:56:35.047
Yeah. Munro. M-U-N-R-O.

891
00:56:35.215 --> 00:56:39.635
Munro. Wait here a minute, sir.

892
00:56:39.803 --> 00:56:41.387
Thank you.

893
00:56:43.807 --> 00:56:45.766
Mr. Munro is here
for that damaged shipment.

894
00:56:45.934 --> 00:56:47.977
- You want me to talk to him?
- Yeah.

895
00:56:49.855 --> 00:56:51.981
- Mr. "Moonro."
- Munro.

896
00:56:52.149 --> 00:56:54.483
- Come with me to the storage area.
- Is there a problem?

897
00:56:54.651 --> 00:56:56.777
Your consignment has suffered some damage.

898
00:56:56.945 --> 00:56:59.071
Oh, no.

899
00:56:59.239 --> 00:57:03.284
Why the heck did I bother to paint
these arrows on the side of it then?

900
00:57:03.451 --> 00:57:05.578
That's the way it was delivered here,
unfortunately.

901
00:57:05.745 --> 00:57:07.079
Well, what happened to it?

902
00:57:07.247 --> 00:57:09.331
My information is that
10 tons of fertilizer...

903
00:57:09.499 --> 00:57:12.585
was inadvertently loaded on top
of your box while it was in the hold.

904
00:57:12.752 --> 00:57:13.961
I'd sue the shipping company.

905
00:57:14.129 --> 00:57:16.797
Sue? I have no time to waste
my blooming life suing anybody.

906
00:57:16.965 --> 00:57:20.384
Get some of your blokes
to pull this right-side up...

907
00:57:20.552 --> 00:57:24.763
so I can get in to the motorcycle
and see what damage has been done.

908
00:57:24.931 --> 00:57:28.642
All right, fellas.
Let's get it unwrapped.

909
00:57:31.438 --> 00:57:33.397
Well, the tire's all right.

910
00:57:38.278 --> 00:57:40.279
No damage so far.

911
00:57:41.615 --> 00:57:44.408
No damage at all. It's good.

912
00:57:44.576 --> 00:57:47.328
- Lucky it was packed so well.
- Yeah. It's a blooming miracle.

913
00:57:49.956 --> 00:57:54.168
Well, the old Indian lives
to fight another day!

914
00:58:00.634 --> 00:58:02.384
Well, thanks a million, Tina.

915
00:58:02.552 --> 00:58:04.512
I don't know what I'd have done
without you today.

916
00:58:04.638 --> 00:58:06.472
You're the real salt of the earth,
you know?

917
00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:09.560
Are you sure you wouldn't like to come
home to mi casa for dinner tonight?

918
00:58:09.684 --> 00:58:11.524
- No, I can't, love.
- I could cook you a meal.

919
00:58:11.603 --> 00:58:14.243
I've gotta get the show on the road,
get out of Dodge, as they say.

920
00:58:14.397 --> 00:58:16.607
Okay, my good friend from kiwi-land.

921
00:58:17.108 --> 00:58:18.817
- You stay in touch, won't you?
- I will.

922
00:58:19.653 --> 00:58:21.237
- Here's my phone number.
- Okay.

923
00:58:21.404 --> 00:58:24.156
- Call me and tell me how you're doing.
- I will. Can I call collect?

924
00:58:24.824 --> 00:58:26.283
You can try.

925
00:58:32.582 --> 00:58:35.501
- It's a good job I think you're a woman.
- I am a woman.

926
00:58:35.669 --> 00:58:38.504
Yeah, right. Ta-ta, love. See you.

927
00:59:05.865 --> 00:59:07.658
- Morning.
- Good morning.

928
00:59:09.369 --> 00:59:11.036
Fill her up, would you, please?

929
00:59:11.204 --> 00:59:13.038
Regular or ethyl?

930
00:59:13.206 --> 00:59:14.873
Who's Ethel?

931
00:59:15.959 --> 00:59:19.128
All right. I'll take ethyl.

932
00:59:25.677 --> 00:59:29.221
- Hi, young fella.
- Hello. Is this a rocket ship?

933
00:59:29.389 --> 00:59:31.890
- What?
- Is this a rocket ship?

934
00:59:32.058 --> 00:59:34.226
I hope so.

935
01:00:13.308 --> 01:00:14.558
Oh, gosh.

936
01:00:21.107 --> 01:00:23.108
What's happened to you?

937
01:00:27.447 --> 01:00:29.365
Oh, well.

938
01:00:32.285 --> 01:00:34.119
Let's have a look at you.

939
01:00:50.470 --> 01:00:51.804
Gotcha!

940
01:00:54.015 --> 01:00:55.766
Hey, come on.

941
01:01:06.986 --> 01:01:09.863
I thought we were gonna
make it, you and me...

942
01:01:10.031 --> 01:01:12.991
and now look what's happened.

943
01:01:13.159 --> 01:01:14.701
Ah.

944
01:02:04.627 --> 01:02:06.795
- Hello, mate.
- Got a problem?

945
01:02:06.963 --> 01:02:10.966
Yeah. Am I glad to see you.
Yeah, I've lost a wheel.

946
01:02:11.134 --> 01:02:12.934
Help me get my rig back
on the road, will you?

947
01:02:13.052 --> 01:02:15.220
Okay, let me see.

948
01:02:15.388 --> 01:02:18.307
My name's Burt. Burt Munro.

949
01:02:18.475 --> 01:02:20.601
- Jake.
- Jake? Are you Indian?

950
01:02:20.768 --> 01:02:22.227
- Yes.
- Yeah.

951
01:02:22.395 --> 01:02:24.730
Well, this here could be
the world's fastest Indian.

952
01:02:24.898 --> 01:02:26.940
Well, at least until just now.

953
01:02:27.108 --> 01:02:28.942
She's a bit heavy, mind you.

954
01:02:29.110 --> 01:02:31.278
Let's take it easy. One, two, three.

955
01:02:33.573 --> 01:02:35.073
You live around here, Jake?

956
01:02:50.340 --> 01:02:52.341
- Burt.
- Huh?

957
01:02:52.509 --> 01:02:55.469
What do you want to ride
that contraption for?

958
01:02:55.637 --> 01:02:59.223
That's a good question. Uh...

959
01:02:59.390 --> 01:03:02.893
I guess the reward is in
the doing of it, you know?

960
01:03:03.061 --> 01:03:04.895
I don't want to go to bed.

961
01:03:05.063 --> 01:03:07.773
Jake, I'm dying for a pee.
Where do I go?

962
01:03:07.941 --> 01:03:09.983
There's a little building back there.

963
01:03:10.151 --> 01:03:13.111
I got a touch of prostate trouble,
you know?

964
01:03:13.279 --> 01:03:14.947
I have similar problems.

965
01:03:15.114 --> 01:03:19.243
Well, I thought you blokes would have
some magic cure for that sort of thing.

966
01:03:19.410 --> 01:03:21.537
- Well, we have.
- Oh, yeah?

967
01:03:21.704 --> 01:03:23.789
One old remedy is ground-up dog balls.

968
01:03:23.957 --> 01:03:26.708
- Oh, good.
- Then you're happy for prostate trouble.

969
01:03:26.876 --> 01:03:28.794
Yeah, I bet you do, mate.

970
01:03:31.881 --> 01:03:33.590
Got you!

971
01:03:34.884 --> 01:03:37.928
Jake, gotta get going.
Gotta hit the road.

972
01:03:38.096 --> 01:03:40.973
- Burt, I have something for you.
- What's that, then?

973
01:03:42.350 --> 01:03:44.977
- What's this?
- For good luck.

974
01:03:45.144 --> 01:03:48.981
Oh, yeah, a piece of...
I've never worn jewelry before.

975
01:03:49.148 --> 01:03:51.984
Thanks, mate.
Oh, I've got something for you too.

976
01:03:53.987 --> 01:03:56.989
Right. Let's see.

977
01:03:58.992 --> 01:04:02.035
Here. I've got this.

978
01:04:02.203 --> 01:04:04.204
It's a spare one. I made it myself.

979
01:04:04.372 --> 01:04:05.497
What do I do with this?

980
01:04:05.665 --> 01:04:07.833
- You got a hacksaw?
- Yeah.

981
01:04:08.001 --> 01:04:11.169
You just slice the top of it through there.
It could also make a great ashtray.

982
01:04:11.337 --> 01:04:13.005
