01:20:09.127 --> 01:20:12.630
You know, all my life,
I've wanted to do something big...

1225
01:20:12.798 --> 01:20:16.008
something bigger and better
than all the other jokers.

1226
01:20:17.219 --> 01:20:19.178
This is it. Bonneville.

1227
01:20:19.346 --> 01:20:24.600
This is the place where big things happen.

1228
01:20:27.396 --> 01:20:32.191
Do you realize, Rusty, the fastest man
has ever gone on land is here?

1229
01:20:32.359 --> 01:20:34.819
Right here, where we are now.

1230
01:20:35.862 --> 01:20:37.154
Huh.

1231
01:20:37.322 --> 01:20:41.409
Malcolm Campbell did it here with Bluebird.

1232
01:20:41.577 --> 01:20:43.953
First guy to go over 300 mile an hour...

1233
01:20:44.121 --> 01:20:46.831
and then later his son Donald Campbell
was here with Proteus.

1234
01:20:46.999 --> 01:20:51.168
He crashed at 350 miles an hour
and lived to tell the tale.

1235
01:20:52.671 --> 01:20:55.172
John Cobb was here.

1236
01:20:55.340 --> 01:20:59.135
First guy to go over 400 miles an hour.

1237
01:20:59.303 --> 01:21:01.554
All the great attempts.

1238
01:21:01.722 --> 01:21:03.681
George Easton with Thunderbolt...

1239
01:21:03.849 --> 01:21:08.519
and Mickey Thompson with Challenger.

1240
01:21:11.481 --> 01:21:15.234
I'm telling you, Rusty,
this place is holy ground, mate.

1241
01:21:15.402 --> 01:21:18.070
Holy ground.

1242
01:21:18.238 --> 01:21:20.531
And I made it here.

1243
01:21:49.728 --> 01:21:51.479
- Well, Burt...
- Yeah?

1244
01:21:51.647 --> 01:21:54.231
Thanks a million. We'll be looking
for you in the record books.

1245
01:21:54.399 --> 01:21:56.567
You take care over there in Vietnam,
won't you?

1246
01:21:56.735 --> 01:21:58.235
I'll be trying.

1247
01:21:58.403 --> 01:21:59.904
- Go ahead, mate.
- Drive safe.

1248
01:22:00.072 --> 01:22:02.198
- See you.
- See you.

1249
01:23:19.151 --> 01:23:20.484
God.

1250
01:23:28.577 --> 01:23:30.161
Oh!

1251
01:23:31.621 --> 01:23:33.581
Thank God.

1252
01:23:48.054 --> 01:23:50.264
Jesus. Yeah.

1253
01:24:22.672 --> 01:24:25.007
- Good day.
- Hey there.

1254
01:24:27.385 --> 01:24:29.178
- It's gonna be a great day.
- Yeah.

1255
01:24:29.346 --> 01:24:32.431
Still. No wind.

1256
01:24:32.599 --> 01:24:34.266
Lovely day for a run.

1257
01:24:36.353 --> 01:24:37.728
Salt's in good shape.

1258
01:24:37.896 --> 01:24:39.897
Yeah. Firm and dry.

1259
01:24:40.065 --> 01:24:42.399
Dead flat, no soft patches.

1260
01:24:42.567 --> 01:24:44.026
Not like the beach.

1261
01:24:45.695 --> 01:24:48.280
Yeah. I can do it here.

1262
01:24:48.448 --> 01:24:52.326
Yep. This week.
That's what we're here for.

1263
01:24:52.994 --> 01:24:54.578
Yeah.

1264
01:24:57.123 --> 01:24:59.124
God, is that yours?

1265
01:24:59.292 --> 01:25:00.376
Yep.

1266
01:25:01.086 --> 01:25:03.587
Oh, she's a beauty.

1267
01:25:03.755 --> 01:25:06.549
I'll bet she goes fast.

1268
01:25:06.716 --> 01:25:09.260
- Is that yours?
- Yeah. It's an old Indian.

1269
01:25:09.719 --> 01:25:12.721
My name is Munro, Burt Munro,
from down under, New Zealand.

1270
01:25:12.889 --> 01:25:14.682
- Long way from home.
- Yeah.

1271
01:25:14.850 --> 01:25:17.142
Jim Moffett, San Jose, California.

1272
01:25:17.310 --> 01:25:19.436
- Nice to meet you, Burt.
- Good to meet you, Jim.

1273
01:25:19.604 --> 01:25:22.857
Next on the
starting line, the Moffett Racing entry...

1274
01:25:25.443 --> 01:25:30.656
Racing Downs. Driven by Jim Moffett,
San Jose, California...

1275
01:25:47.674 --> 01:25:49.592
Come on, let's go.

1276
01:25:57.809 --> 01:26:00.144
- Morning.
- Hello. Burt Munro.

1277
01:26:00.312 --> 01:26:01.645
- Mike.
- Mike?

1278
01:26:01.813 --> 01:26:03.898
Are you checked in?

1279
01:26:04.065 --> 01:26:05.733
No. Not yet.

1280
01:26:05.901 --> 01:26:09.361
Well, you know, you gotta remove the
shell before we do the tech inspection.

1281
01:26:09.529 --> 01:26:11.113
Where do I check in?

1282
01:26:11.281 --> 01:26:13.115
- It's just over there.
- Thanks, fellas.

1283
01:26:13.283 --> 01:26:15.075
- Okay.
- Thank you.

1284
01:26:16.828 --> 01:26:18.203
Gotta see this.

1285
01:26:18.371 --> 01:26:20.497
Hello. I've come to check in.

1286
01:26:20.665 --> 01:26:21.999
Munro. Burt Munro.

1287
01:26:22.167 --> 01:26:25.502
- Registration number?
- What?

1288
01:26:25.670 --> 01:26:28.339
Registration number.
I don't see your number here.

1289
01:26:29.341 --> 01:26:32.176
Oh, no, it's 35.

1290
01:26:32.344 --> 01:26:34.887
It's on the side
of my motorcycle over there.

1291
01:26:35.055 --> 01:26:38.015
- That's my lucky number.
- Have you registered?

1292
01:26:39.267 --> 01:26:41.727
No. That's what I come for.

1293
01:26:41.895 --> 01:26:44.521
These two blokes sent me over here.
Mike and someone else.

1294
01:26:44.689 --> 01:26:46.482
Sir, registration closed last month.

1295
01:26:46.650 --> 01:26:50.819
If you haven't registered, I'm sorry,
you just can't run.

1296
01:26:53.490 --> 01:26:56.241
I can't run? I mean, uh...

1297
01:26:56.409 --> 01:26:59.078
Well, how was I supposed to know
I should have pre-registered?

1298
01:26:59.245 --> 01:27:01.705
I mean, I've come a heck of a long way
to run my bike.

1299
01:27:01.873 --> 01:27:04.208
You know, I'm not going anywhere
until I've done just that.

1300
01:27:04.376 --> 01:27:07.378
I've come all the way from New Zealand,
you know? It's a long way.

1301
01:27:07.545 --> 01:27:09.065
Look, mister, we don't make the rules.

1302
01:27:09.214 --> 01:27:12.049
You know, an event like this doesn't
just happen in one day.

1303
01:27:12.217 --> 01:27:14.218
Rules are rules.
Entries closed July 31 st.

1304
01:27:14.386 --> 01:27:15.844
But, crikey, I live in Invercargill.

1305
01:27:16.012 --> 01:27:18.222
It's halfway around the bloody Earth,
you know?

1306
01:27:18.390 --> 01:27:20.307
How was I supposed to know these things?

1307
01:27:20.475 --> 01:27:22.915
- I didn't know all this stuff.
- Sir, that's not our problem.

1308
01:27:23.019 --> 01:27:25.339
I thought I could just turn up here
and have my bike timed.

1309
01:27:25.480 --> 01:27:27.389
You don't have to call me "sir."
My name's Munro.

1310
01:27:27.399 --> 01:27:29.024
Well, sir, you thought wrong.

1311
01:27:37.701 --> 01:27:40.494
Here, Jim. Jim Moffett!

1312
01:27:40.662 --> 01:27:43.163
It's Burt Munro.
Could you come over here, mate?

1313
01:27:43.331 --> 01:27:45.749
Hey, I'll be right back.

1314
01:27:45.917 --> 01:27:47.126
I need a bit of help.

1315
01:27:47.293 --> 01:27:49.461
Hey, Burt. What's up?

1316
01:27:49.629 --> 01:27:50.921
Well, I need your help.

1317
01:27:51.089 --> 01:27:53.382
These blokes are telling me
I can't run my bike...

1318
01:27:53.550 --> 01:27:55.384
because I'm not pre-registered.

1319
01:27:55.552 --> 01:27:57.970
- You didn't register?
- No. I didn't know anything about it.

1320
01:27:58.138 --> 01:28:01.098
You know how it is, Jim.
Rules are rules.

1321
01:28:01.266 --> 01:28:03.017
Burt, you should have
registered months ago.

1322
01:28:03.184 --> 01:28:04.810
I didn't know.

1323
01:28:04.978 --> 01:28:08.105
Look, I'll have a talk with these guys later,
see if I can change their minds.

1324
01:28:08.273 --> 01:28:11.191
- Blood's worth bottling.
- I don't know about that.

1325
01:28:11.359 --> 01:28:13.944
Look, we can talk about this later.

1326
01:28:14.112 --> 01:28:17.656
Maybe you can let him go through
tech inspection, get that out of the way.

1327
01:28:17.824 --> 01:28:19.658
Just in case we can let him run.

1328
01:28:19.826 --> 01:28:21.577
You're asking a lot.

1329
01:28:23.121 --> 01:28:25.205
Right.

1330
01:28:27.792 --> 01:28:28.792
Okay.

1331
01:28:28.960 --> 01:28:30.210
- All right.
- What?

1332
01:28:30.378 --> 01:28:32.296
- Make me proud.
- Thanks a lot.

1333
01:28:32.464 --> 01:28:35.257
Gave me a bit of a fight there.

1334
01:28:39.137 --> 01:28:42.264
You know, these don't look
like high-speed tires.

1335
01:28:42.432 --> 01:28:44.850
Well, they are high-speed tires.

1336
01:28:45.018 --> 01:28:48.312
Look at these hairline cracks.
These tires gotta be 25 years old.

1337
01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:50.731
- What happened to the tread?
- What?

1338
01:28:50.899 --> 01:28:53.067
- I said, what happened to the tread?
- I cut it off.

1339
01:28:53.234 --> 01:28:55.434
That's what happened.
I cut it off with a carving knife.

1340
01:28:55.570 --> 01:28:57.821
Otherwise, it wouldn't be
a high-speed tire, would it?

1341
01:28:57.989 --> 01:28:59.198
What are you talking about?

1342
01:28:59.365 --> 01:29:01.325
You got to keep the weight down,
haven't you, son?

1343
01:29:01.493 --> 01:29:03.994
Or when you get it to a high speed,
the centrifugal force...

1344
01:29:04.162 --> 01:29:05.662
would throw the tread right off.

1345
01:29:05.830 --> 01:29:09.500
I run them on 65 pounds of air.
That tire's safe up to 300 mile an hour.

1346
01:29:09.667 --> 01:29:12.503
I guarantee it. These are high-speed tires,
and I made them.

1347
01:29:12.670 --> 01:29:16.215
Well, you're gonna have to replace them.
The suspension here is a leaf-spring.

1348
01:29:16.382 --> 01:29:17.674
I mean, can we pass that?

1349
01:29:17.842 --> 01:29:21.011
Jeez, last leaf-spring on a motorcycle
must have been in the 1920s.

1350
01:29:21.179 --> 01:29:22.721
Well, it is 42 years old.

1351
01:29:22.889 --> 01:29:24.515
These brakes are completely inadequate.

1352
01:29:24.682 --> 01:29:26.934
I'm planning on going, not stopping.
Ha, ha, ha.

1353
01:29:27.102 --> 01:29:29.103
The brakes were old-fashioned 40 years ago.

1354
01:29:29.270 --> 01:29:32.481
- Yeah.
- Is this a hinge off a fence post?

1355
01:29:32.649 --> 01:29:34.858
No. That's from an old kitchen door.

1356
01:29:37.445 --> 01:29:40.364
Let me just ask you, what is this?

1357
01:29:40.532 --> 01:29:43.293
It's a cork. What does it look like?
It's a cork from a brandy bottle.

1358
01:29:43.451 --> 01:29:47.746
The thing is, it's all about weight.
The less weight, the faster you go.

1359
01:29:47.914 --> 01:29:50.040
- Where's your chute?
- What?

1360
01:29:50.208 --> 01:29:52.793
- Where's your parachute?
- I'm not planning on bailing out.

1361
01:29:52.961 --> 01:29:56.547
- No. You've got to have a safety chute.
- I can't afford one.

1362
01:29:57.382 --> 01:30:00.092
These forks, if they give out,
we got ourselves a real problem.

1363
01:30:00.260 --> 01:30:03.345
I think I'd have a bit of a problem
that way, wouldn't I?

1364
01:30:03.513 --> 01:30:04.793
- Where's your fire suit?
- What?

1365
01:30:04.931 --> 01:30:06.098
Where's your fire suit?

1366
01:30:06.266 --> 01:30:08.809
Good heavens, man.
I don't intend to burst into flames.

1367
01:30:08.977 --> 01:30:11.436
Always wear my
old suit pants for good luck.

1368
01:30:11.604 --> 01:30:15.149
If they were good enough to get married in,
they're good enough to ride this old girl in.

1369
01:30:15.316 --> 01:30:18.735
And, you know, I just tuck the legs of my
pants into my socks like this, you know...

1370
01:30:18.903 --> 01:30:21.655
stop them getting caught in the chain
and Bob's your uncle.

1371
01:30:21.823 --> 01:30:23.143
Okay. So you got your suit pants.

1372
01:30:23.283 --> 01:30:24.950
- What are you gonna wear on top?
- What?

1373
01:30:25.118 --> 01:30:28.078
You got your suit pants on the bottom.
What do you intend to wear on top?

1374
01:30:28.246 --> 01:30:31.915
Yes, a black woolen shirt,
New Zealand wool, water-resistant...

1375
01:30:32.083 --> 01:30:34.168
fire-resistant, and me bash hat.

1376
01:30:34.335 --> 01:30:36.753
- Your bash hat?
- Bash hat.

1377
01:30:36.921 --> 01:30:38.463
- Crash helmet.
- You're crazy.

1378
01:30:38.631 --> 01:30:41.091
You gotta wear, like,
at least a leather jacket on top.

1379
01:30:41.259 --> 01:30:44.261
You put the bike down on the salt,
it's like coarse sandpaper.

1380
01:30:44.429 --> 01:30:47.269
- It's gonna rub your head right off.
- I couldn't get into the shell...

1381
01:30:47.432 --> 01:30:49.558
with anything bulkier
than the shirt on my back.

1382
01:30:49.726 --> 01:30:52.603
- I mean, it's a very tight fit in there.
- Straight out of the ark.

1383
01:30:52.770 --> 01:30:55.689
- What did you say?
- Straight out of the ark.

1384
01:30:55.857 --> 01:30:58.442
Why are you being so cheeky?
What's your name, young man?

1385
01:30:58.610 --> 01:31:01.195
McFarland. Mike McFarland.

1386
01:31:01.362 --> 01:31:04.031
I knew a McFarland. He used
to sell milking machines in Timaru.

1387
01:31:04.199 --> 01:31:06.825
You must be related to him
because he was a total prick.

1388
01:31:06.993 --> 01:31:09.453
You don't even have
a fire extinguisher installed.

1389
01:31:09.621 --> 01:31:12.789
Mike McFarland used to give me
milking-machine parts...

1390
01:31:12.957 --> 01:31:15.834
- to make my sprockets with.
- Just how old are you?

1391
01:31:16.002 --> 01:31:17.961
I don't know.
He was about 35 when I knew...

1392
01:31:18.129 --> 01:31:19.129
No. How old are you?

1393
01:31:19.297 --> 01:31:22.716
His brother owned the general store,
down at a place called Bulls.

1394
01:31:22.884 --> 01:31:25.844
- That's a town in New Zealand.
- Sir, your machine is not safe.

1395
01:31:26.012 --> 01:31:28.847
I've been doing this for 43 years,
and I'm still here to tell the tale.

1396
01:31:29.015 --> 01:31:32.351
Well, times change. We started taking
airplanes instead of riding horseback.

1397
01:31:32.518 --> 01:31:34.144
- Horsepower?
- Horseback.

1398
01:31:34.312 --> 01:31:36.313
Horseback. Yeah, I got you. Yeah.

1399
01:31:36.481 --> 01:31:38.232
You're too old.

1400
01:31:38.399 --> 01:31:40.984
Bollocks. I may have this
saggy skin on the outside...

1401
01:31:41.152 --> 01:31:42.832
but inside, I'm still 18 years old.

1402
01:31:42.862 --> 01:31:46.573
I'd give you a run for your money,
young fella.

1403
01:31:46.741 --> 01:31:50.077
- Need some help?
- Oh, hello.

1404
01:31:50.245 --> 01:31:53.372
Rolly Freed, Marty Dickerson.
We're a couple of bike fans.

1405
01:31:53.539 --> 01:31:55.666
Oh. Burt Munro from kiwi-land.

1406
01:31:55.833 --> 01:31:57.501
A pleasure, Burt.

1407
01:31:59.128 --> 01:32:00.754
- You got me good there.
- Yeah.

1408
01:32:00.922 --> 01:32:02.172
Where are you staying?

1409
01:32:02.340 --> 01:32:04.508
Well, that's my salubrious accommodation.

1410
01:32:04.676 --> 01:32:07.344
I usually sleep at night in the back seat.

1411
01:32:07.512 --> 01:32:09.596
Salubrious, you say, Munro, huh?

1412
01:32:09.764 --> 01:32:11.556
We been hearing a lot about you.

1413
01:32:11.724 --> 01:32:13.934
Sounds like you're cutting
your finances mighty fine.

1414
01:32:14.102 --> 01:32:15.686
Oh, yeah. You can say that again.

1415
01:32:15.853 --> 01:32:18.272
Well, we're up at the Western Ridge.
Why don't you drop by?

1416
01:32:18.439 --> 01:32:21.191
Looks like you could use a shower
and everybody's staying there...

1417
01:32:21.359 --> 01:32:23.527
and I bet that there's
a spare bed there too.

1418
01:32:23.695 --> 01:32:25.988
Well, thanks a lot.
You Yanks are classic, you know that?

1419
01:32:26.155 --> 01:32:29.157
You don't catch me that easily.

1420
01:32:34.372 --> 01:32:35.872
Hey, Burt.

1421
01:32:36.040 --> 01:32:37.249
Hello.

1422
01:32:39.210 --> 01:32:43.714
The front forks could go at any time,
the suspension is right out of the 1920s...

1423
01:32:43.881 --> 01:32:46.049
he's got hairline cracks
all over his tires...

1424
01:32:46.217 --> 01:32:49.219
he's got no fire extinguisher,
no safety chute.

1425
01:32:49.387 --> 01:32:52.639
I told you, if it's a time problem, the old
guy's welcome to use some of my time.

1426
01:32:52.807 --> 01:32:55.017
It's not a time problem,
it's a bike problem.

1427
01:32:55.184 --> 01:32:56.935
Well, I think we ought to let him run.

1428
01:32:57.103 --> 01:32:59.730
He came all the way from
New Zealand to do this.

1429
01:32:59.897 --> 01:33:01.982
Jim, have you had a good look
at his machine?

1430
01:33:02.150 --> 01:33:04.693
All I know is,
the man's the genuine article.

1431
01:33:04.861 --> 01:33:06.778
Well, the bike is a genuine dinosaur.

1432
01:33:06.946 --> 01:33:09.448
Look, we carry the can
for the decisions around here.

1433
01:33:09.615 --> 01:33:12.655
If the old fart kills himself...
And it's about 100-to-1 that he will, right?

1434
01:33:12.744 --> 01:33:15.746
We are gonna have a hell of a lot
of trouble on our hands.

1435
01:33:15.913 --> 01:33:19.958
Yeah. It sounds like we're a bunch
of chickenshits, if you want my opinion.

1436
01:33:20.126 --> 01:33:24.880
His bike didn't even come close
to passing tech inspection, Jim.

1437
01:33:33.890 --> 01:33:37.100
- Burt.
- Hello, Jim. Come in.

1438
01:33:37.268 --> 01:33:39.061
Rolly Freed said I could find you here.

1439
01:33:39.228 --> 01:33:41.980
Rolly Freed, yeah. Ah, he's the best.
He's a real gentleman.

1440
01:33:42.148 --> 01:33:45.275
You know, he set me up
at this place for nothing.

1441
01:33:48.112 --> 01:33:49.279
What are you doing?

1442
01:33:49.447 --> 01:33:51.907
Well, the soft shoe polish
fills in the cracks...

1443
01:33:52.075 --> 01:33:54.451
makes the tires look spic and span...

1444
01:33:54.619 --> 01:33:56.787
good as new and cheaper
than new ones, anyway.

1445
01:33:57.497 --> 01:33:59.122
I didn't see that.

1446
01:34:01.417 --> 01:34:03.794
Well, can I run?

1447
01:34:06.130 --> 01:34:07.631
I'm sorry, Burt.

1448
01:34:14.639 --> 01:34:17.474
Who the heck do they think they are?

1449
01:34:17.642 --> 01:34:21.269
Crikey, Jim, you know,
I'm not trying to run a mile in four minutes.

1450
01:34:21.437 --> 01:34:24.064
All I've got to do is sit there
and open up the throttle.

1451
01:34:24.232 --> 01:34:27.734
I mean, after all,
it's my ruddy life, isn't it?

1452
01:34:28.694 --> 01:34:30.821
Can't you do anything?

1453
01:34:30.988 --> 01:34:34.783
I mean, I just want to try and get her
to go over 200 just once, that's all.

1454
01:34:34.951 --> 01:34:35.992
Once I've cracked 200...

1455
01:34:36.160 --> 01:34:39.480
I'll be quite happy to piss off back home
to New Zealand and Bob's your uncle.

1456
01:34:40.206 --> 01:34:43.542
You're a well-respected man, aren't you?
Couldn't you talk to them?

1457
01:34:44.377 --> 01:34:45.585
I tried.

1458
01:34:46.212 --> 01:34:48.922
I mean, you've got as much chance
of writing yourself off as I have.

1459
01:34:49.090 --> 01:34:52.259
You know that. Just talk to them again.

1460
01:34:53.678 --> 01:34:55.637
I know they'll listen to you, mate.

1461
01:34:57.890 --> 01:35:00.225
Okay, Burt, I'll try.

1462
01:35:00.393 --> 01:35:02.144
- See you tomorrow.
- Okay.

1463
01:35:05.690 --> 01:35:09.276
I mean, I'm half the age of some
of those characters out there.

1464
01:35:14.740 --> 01:35:19.453
- What's that?
- Oh, that's just indigestion.

1465
01:35:24.125 --> 01:35:25.876
You see, everyone wants us old buggers...

1466
01:35:26.043 --> 01:35:29.713
to curl up in some quiet corner and die.

1467
01:35:29.881 --> 01:35:34.551
Well, Burt Munro is not ready to finish yet,
I'll tell you that, mate.

1468
01:35:36.387 --> 01:35:38.889
I'll give it a shot,
but I'm not promising anything.

1469
01:35:39.056 --> 01:35:41.766
Thanks, mate. Thanks a lot.

1470
01:35:46.731 --> 01:35:50.358
The famous
Mickey Johnson car, Challenger I.

1471
01:35:59.410 --> 01:36:03.163
- Where's he going?
- Didn't Jim tell him?

1472
01:36:03.331 --> 01:36:05.999
- He says he did.
- Then what's he doing here?

1473
01:36:06.167 --> 01:36:07.250
Why won't you let him run?

1474
01:36:07.418 --> 01:36:09.753
Hey, he's too old and his bike's too old.

1475
01:36:09.921 --> 01:36:12.297
I hear he come halfway around the world
to ride that cycle.

1476
01:36:12.465 --> 01:36:13.882
Yeah. Come on.

1477
01:36:14.050 --> 01:36:15.842
Wendy, if he was to kill himself...

1478
01:36:16.010 --> 01:36:18.637
So? It's his life.

1479
01:36:18.804 --> 01:36:21.097
Keep an eye out for those officials.

1480
01:36:21.265 --> 01:36:23.266
You sure?
I don't think it's such a good idea.

1481
01:36:23.434 --> 01:36:25.727
If we're gonna do this damn thing,
you gotta hurry.

1482
01:36:25.895 --> 01:36:28.563
All right. Let's go.
Here's your helmet.

1483
01:36:29.607 --> 01:36:31.775
Here's your goggles.

1484
01:36:31.943 --> 01:36:34.069
- Come on, Burt. We gotta go.
- Yeah, right.

1485
01:36:34.237 --> 01:36:36.196
Put them on. Put them on.

1486
01:36:39.992 --> 01:36:41.993
Go! Come on!

1487
01:36:45.331 --> 01:36:47.040
Okay, let's go.

1488
01:36:47.208 --> 01:36:49.125
Push. Go fast!

1489
01:36:49.293 --> 01:36:51.461
Hey, you can't... Hey! You can't do that!

1490
01:36:51.629 --> 01:36:53.296
Come on! Come on!

1491
01:36:53.464 --> 01:36:55.131
Whoa! Hey! Whoa!

1492
01:36:55.299 --> 01:36:56.967
Hang on! Whoa!

1493
01:36:59.971 --> 01:37:02.013
Hey, where are you going with that?

1494
01:37:06.936 --> 01:37:09.854
Stop! Stop, stop, stop.

1495
01:37:10.022 --> 01:37:12.148
What the hell are you doing, Burt?

1496
01:37:12.316 --> 01:37:15.694
- What the hell are you doing?
- Just getting her warmed up, Bob.

1497
01:37:15.861 --> 01:37:17.520
Didn't look like you were
getting her warmed up.

1498
01:37:17.530 --> 01:37:19.656
Jesus. He was gonna take
the thing for a fricking run.

1499
01:37:19.824 --> 01:37:22.200
Bob. Oh, boy.

1500
01:37:22.368 --> 01:37:24.160
Okay.

1501
01:37:24.328 --> 01:37:26.621
That is the most determined man
I've ever seen in my life.

1502
01:37:26.789 --> 01:37:28.164
Yeah.

1503
01:37:28.332 --> 01:37:31.334
I kind of feel sorry for the old coot...

1504
01:37:31.502 --> 01:37:34.170
coming all this way, huh?

1505
01:37:34.338 --> 01:37:36.172
Isn't there some way we can
accommodate him?

1506
01:37:36.340 --> 01:37:37.841
There can't be much risk there.

1507
01:37:38.009 --> 01:37:42.178
His bike will be lucky if it does 70.
What do you say?

1508
01:37:42.346 --> 01:37:46.057
Why don't we bend the rules this once, huh?

1509
01:37:47.351 --> 01:37:48.393
Jesus.

1510
01:37:48.561 --> 01:37:50.562
- Burt.
- Yeah?

1511
01:37:51.689 --> 01:37:53.773
Bob and I had a little chat...

1512
01:37:53.941 --> 01:37:57.068
and we're thinking we're gonna
organize a handling run for you.

1513
01:37:57.236 --> 01:38:00.322
- You are? What?
- Well, a handling run.

1514
01:38:00.489 --> 01:38:02.649
All the officials, we're gonna
get into our vehicles...

1515
01:38:02.742 --> 01:38:04.034
- You're joking.
- No, I'm not.

1516
01:38:04.201 --> 01:38:08.038
We're gonna follow along behind you
and see if you're okay to ride this beast.

1517
01:38:08.205 --> 01:38:09.539
Of course I'm okay to ride it.

1518
01:38:09.707 --> 01:38:12.542
First thing tomorrow morning, all right?
Bright and early.

1519
01:38:14.503 --> 01:38:16.963
Thanks, fellas.

1520
01:38:17.131 --> 01:38:19.674
I'll see you, then.

1521
01:38:22.553 --> 01:38:23.720
- Are you all right?
- Yeah.

1522
01:38:23.888 --> 01:38:25.347
Don't hurt yourself.

1523
01:38:36.567 --> 01:38:39.944
Okay, everyone listen up!
This is what we're gonna do!

1524
01:38:40.112 --> 01:38:42.572
Burt, you're gonna get rolling, all right?

1525
01:38:42.740 --> 01:38:46.576
Ride slowly along. We'll all jump in our
vehicles, follow you down the track.

1526
01:38:46.744 --> 01:38:49.264
- See if you can handle this thing.
- I'll handle her all right.

1527
01:38:49.330 --> 01:38:50.914
All right. Everybody got that?

1528
01:38:51.082 --> 01:38:54.834
Okay. Let's get in the cars.

1529
01:38:56.671 --> 01:38:58.254
All right. Sounds good.

1530
01:39:17.858 --> 01:39:20.360
Hope the old man doesn't
make a fool of himself.

1531
01:39:24.990 --> 01:39:27.283
- Here we go.
- In here. Okay.

1532
01:39:27.451 --> 01:39:30.870
Right-o. I'm ready. Let's go!
Go ahead, push it!

1533
01:39:31.038 --> 01:39:32.664
Come on! Push it, boys!

1534
01:39:35.042 --> 01:39:36.876
- Go, Burt!
- Whoa!

1535
01:40:00.025 --> 01:40:03.528
Sixty, 65, 70.

1536
01:40:04.905 --> 01:40:06.364
Attaboy, Burt!

1537
01:40:06.532 --> 01:40:07.949
Seventy-five.

1538
01:40:08.117 --> 01:40:11.411
There he goes, up to 80, 85.

1539
01:40:15.499 --> 01:40:16.499
Ninety.

1540
01:40:24.508 --> 01:40:26.843
Ninety-five. Look at that man go!

1541
01:40:37.480 --> 01:40:40.315
- Holy smoke!
- He's leaving them behind!

1542
01:40:40.483 --> 01:40:41.941
What the hell is that old guy up to?

1543
01:40:42.109 --> 01:40:43.829
Nobody told him he
could give it everything.

1544
01:40:43.986 --> 01:40:46.321
Well, that solves the question
of whether he can handle it.

1545
01:40:46.489 --> 01:40:49.616
I'm doing 95, and he left us in the dust.

1546
01:40:49.784 --> 01:40:52.035
- Way to go!
- Attaboy, Burt!

1547
01:41:31.200 --> 01:41:33.243
All right. Grab hold of her.

1548
01:41:33.410 --> 01:41:35.328
Got enough room? Got it?

1549
01:41:35.496 --> 01:41:37.622
Don't let her go.

1550
01:41:37.790 --> 01:41:39.749
Oh, that was a disaster.

1551
01:41:39.917 --> 01:41:42.544
Hey, Burt, how'd it go?

1552
01:41:42.711 --> 01:41:43.753
Not good.

1553
01:41:47.550 --> 01:41:49.968
So, what's the verdict?

1554
01:41:50.135 --> 01:41:52.929
When you opened up there in top gear,
you sure left us in the dust.

1555
01:41:53.097 --> 01:41:55.098
I couldn't even get it out of second gear.

1556
01:41:55.266 --> 01:41:57.267
The plugs were oiling up, so I had to...

1557
01:41:57.434 --> 01:41:59.894
feed it some more juice, you know,
up the revs a little.

1558
01:42:00.062 --> 01:42:03.940
Well, I guess we'll see if you're
telling us the truth, Munro.

1559
01:42:05.150 --> 01:42:08.111
You telling me I can officially run
my bike on the track and have it timed?

1560
01:42:08.279 --> 01:42:10.530
That's what I'm saying, Burt.

1561
01:42:11.699 --> 01:42:14.784
You'll never know what this
means to me, Otto.

1562
01:42:14.952 --> 01:42:18.538
Twenty-five years I've dreamed
of this day. Twenty-five years.

1563
01:42:18.706 --> 01:42:20.456
Sometimes you gotta
bend the rules a little.

1564
01:42:20.624 --> 01:42:21.875
Today's one of those days.

1565
01:42:22.042 --> 01:42:24.836
Thank you from the bottom
of my heart. Thank you.

1566
01:42:25.004 --> 01:42:26.880
Hey, Burt!

1567
01:42:27.047 --> 01:42:29.132
- Burt.
- What?

1568
01:42:30.593 --> 01:42:32.719
- Oh.
- What did they say?

1569
01:42:32.887 --> 01:42:34.429
What happened?

1570
01:42:34.597 --> 01:42:36.806
Well, they said I could run.

1571
01:42:36.974 --> 01:42:40.101
- That's great!
- Yeah.

1572
01:42:40.269 --> 01:42:42.645
- So why the long face, then?
- Well, I don't know.

1573
01:42:42.813 --> 01:42:45.857
It's just starting to sink in,
and I've got a problem, a big problem.

1574
01:42:46.025 --> 01:42:49.652
As soon as I get over 110,
it starts to wobble like heck.

1575
01:42:49.820 --> 01:42:51.154
I mean, a bad speed wobble.

1576
01:42:51.322 --> 01:42:53.922
Well, Burt, it looked like it was
about as stable as my last wife.

1577
01:42:54.033 --> 01:42:56.326
Yeah.

1578
01:42:56.493 --> 01:42:58.828
I've got a theory, and I think I'm right.

1579
01:42:58.996 --> 01:43:01.873
I need about 20 car batteries.

1580
01:43:02.041 --> 01:43:03.458
- Twenty?
- Yeah.

1581
01:43:03.626 --> 01:43:05.793
You think it's okay to steal
these batteries, Burt?

1582
01:43:05.961 --> 01:43:08.121
We're not stealing them, Marty,
we're souveniring them.

1583
01:43:08.255 --> 01:43:12.008
Be careful of that acid right there.
All right. What do we do with them now?

1584
01:43:12.176 --> 01:43:15.470
Well, we've got to talk someone into
lending us a painter's blowtorch.

1585
01:43:15.638 --> 01:43:17.180
A painter's blowtorch?

1586
01:43:19.266 --> 01:43:21.643
What are we gonna do
with all this metal, Burt?

1587
01:43:21.810 --> 01:43:26.898
Well, when this cools down,
we'll have ourselves a lead brick.

1588
01:43:27.066 --> 01:43:28.816
What do you do with a lead brick?

1589
01:43:28.984 --> 01:43:31.402
Place it in the front of the motorcycle.

1590
01:43:31.570 --> 01:43:33.029
And that's your plan?

1591
01:43:33.197 --> 01:43:34.322
Yeah.

1592
01:43:35.824 --> 01:43:37.992
Well, you must get
the center of pressure...

1593
01:43:38.160 --> 01:43:40.903
behind the center of gravity,
and if you don't get it right...

1594
01:43:40.913 --> 01:43:43.748
then she'll start to fishtail
as soon as you get her wound up.

1595
01:43:43.916 --> 01:43:45.375
What do you mean by fishtail?

1596
01:43:45.542 --> 01:43:49.045
Well, like a fish's behind, you know.
You'll start doing that...

1597
01:43:49.213 --> 01:43:51.733
and that's what happened today
when I had the handling run.

1598
01:43:51.882 --> 01:43:55.843
And so, in a panic, I lifted my head up
from behind the screen...

1599
01:43:56.011 --> 01:43:59.430
and suddenly the bike
started to go straight...

1600
01:43:59.598 --> 01:44:02.392
and I knew somehow that
I'd solved the problem...

1601
01:44:02.559 --> 01:44:05.103
by sticking my head up into the wind.

1602
01:44:05.270 --> 01:44:06.813
- I don't get it.
- Me neither.

1603
01:44:06.981 --> 01:44:08.501
Well, I'll show you. Let me have that.

1604
01:44:08.649 --> 01:44:11.818
Hey, give me... What are you doing?

1605
01:44:11.986 --> 01:44:16.364
Now, imagine this cigar is my Streamliner.

1606
01:44:16.532 --> 01:44:17.812
You don't poke holes in a cigar.

1607
01:44:17.908 --> 01:44:21.244
Now, if I hold it in the middle
and blow on it like so...

1608
01:44:22.663 --> 01:44:24.914
See how unstable it is?

1609
01:44:25.082 --> 01:44:29.127
- Now, if I shift...
- Not again.

1610
01:44:29.294 --> 01:44:32.255
the center of pressure here,
and blow on it...

1611
01:44:36.927 --> 01:44:40.763
See? It's much more stable.
See, the center of pressure...

1612
01:44:40.931 --> 01:44:42.765
is behind the center of gravity...

1613
01:44:42.933 --> 01:44:45.453
and that's what I'm trying to fix
with the lead brick, see?

1614
01:44:45.519 --> 01:44:47.311
You're quite clever, Burt, you know that?

1615
01:44:47.479 --> 01:44:51.315
Now all I need to do is to test my theory
before I run on the salt...

1616
01:44:51.483 --> 01:44:54.277
and I was thinking of crossing
over the state line...

1617
01:44:54.445 --> 01:44:57.864
from here in Utah into Nevada
where there's no speed limit...

1618
01:44:58.032 --> 01:45:00.700
and running the bike with a lead brick
in the front of it.

1619
01:45:50.459 --> 01:45:52.668
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

1620
01:45:52.836 --> 01:45:54.556
You know how fast you were
going back there?

1621
01:45:54.671 --> 01:45:59.217
Yeah. About 150,
160 miles an hour.

1622
01:46:00.594 --> 01:46:03.846
- Yeah.
- Yeah, that sounds about right.

1623
01:46:04.014 --> 01:46:06.724
How's he gonna talk his way
out of this one?

1624
01:46:07.684 --> 01:46:10.728
He's sure got his ass in a sling
this time, don't he?

1625
01:46:10.896 --> 01:46:14.357
So, what's the situation with this thing?
You don't have any license plates on it.

1626
01:46:14.525 --> 01:46:17.860
- Well, it's registered in New Zealand.
- New Zealand?

1627
01:46:18.028 --> 01:46:20.863
Yeah. That's where I come from.

1628
01:46:23.659 --> 01:46:26.911
Right. You mean to tell me that
this contraption of yours...

1629
01:46:27.079 --> 01:46:28.454
is registered for the road?

1630
01:46:28.622 --> 01:46:30.581
Yeah, in New Zealand.

1631
01:46:30.749 --> 01:46:32.542
New Zealand. Right.

1632
01:46:32.709 --> 01:46:35.753
Well, how about taking it easy
here in Nevada?

1633
01:46:35.921 --> 01:46:37.681
Just because we don't have a speed limit...

1634
01:46:37.798 --> 01:46:39.758
don't mean we want people
killing themselves.

1635
01:46:40.217 --> 01:46:44.053
- Right, sounds fair enough to me.
- All right. You have a good day.

1636
01:46:44.221 --> 01:46:45.721
- I will. Thank you.
- You bet.

1637
01:46:45.889 --> 01:46:47.765
Burt, everything okay?

1638
01:46:48.809 --> 01:46:50.560
Well, fellas...

1639
01:46:50.727 --> 01:46:55.064
we're gonna have to give the lead brick
the old Spanish archer.

1640
01:46:55.232 --> 01:46:58.901
- Spanish archer?
- Yeah, the big elbow, you know?

1641
01:46:59.069 --> 01:47:03.197
The lead brick has got to go.
Whose stupid idea was that, anyway?

1642
01:47:03.365 --> 01:47:04.448
It was yours.

1643
01:47:04.616 --> 01:47:09.745
Yeah, well, I'm just gonna
have to ride her the way she is.

1644
01:47:09.913 --> 01:47:11.581
What about that speed wobble?

1645
01:47:11.748 --> 01:47:15.418
Well, I'll cross that bridge
when I get there.

1646
01:47:15.586 --> 01:47:18.045
- I've got another problem, too.
- Yeah? What now?

1647
01:47:18.213 --> 01:47:22.758
Well, when I get her going,
there's an enormous amount of heat...

1648
01:47:22.926 --> 01:47:28.764
coming off the exhaust pipe,
and I hope it doesn't cook my leg.

1649
01:47:28.932 --> 01:47:31.726
Maybe you could wrap your leg
in some asbestos cloth.

1650
01:47:31.894 --> 01:47:34.437
- That should fix it, shouldn't it?
- Yeah. That's a good idea.

1651
01:47:34.605 --> 01:47:37.273
So you got any more problems
you want to tell us about?

1652
01:47:37.441 --> 01:47:39.442
Oh, yes. My old ticker.

1653
01:47:39.610 --> 01:47:41.360
You got a bad heart?

1654
01:47:41.528 --> 01:47:43.029
Yes, I have.

1655
01:47:45.199 --> 01:47:46.991
- Hey, Burt.
- Yeah?

1656
01:47:47.159 --> 01:47:49.785
- I've got a little surprise for you.
- What?

1657
01:47:49.953 --> 01:47:51.787
Close your eyes and give me your hand.

1658
01:47:51.955 --> 01:47:54.457
- What?
- Just close your eyes. Come on.

1659
01:47:54.625 --> 01:47:57.710
- What for?
- Because I said so, mister. Come on.

1660
01:47:59.838 --> 01:48:01.297
Just keep walking.

1661
01:48:01.465 --> 01:48:04.926
Wendy, you're not gonna make a fool
out of an old man, now.

1662
01:48:05.093 --> 01:48:06.302
I'd never do that.

1663
01:48:06.470 --> 01:48:08.471
- No?
- Never.

1664
01:48:08.639 --> 01:48:11.349
Never. Okay. Okay. Now turn around.

1665
01:48:11.516 --> 01:48:13.017
- Yeah?
- All right.

1666
01:48:13.185 --> 01:48:14.977
- All right?
- Now hold your hands out.

1667
01:48:15.145 --> 01:48:16.145
- Yeah?
- Good.

1668
01:48:16.313 --> 01:48:18.147
- Put that in your pocket.
- All right.

1669
01:48:18.315 --> 01:48:20.149
- There you go. Good.
- What are you doing?

1670
01:48:20.317 --> 01:48:23.152
Okay. You can open them.

1671
01:48:37.668 --> 01:48:39.460
What are you all staring at?

1672
01:48:41.797 --> 01:48:42.880
What is this?

1673
01:48:43.048 --> 01:48:45.675
Burt, we've unanimously voted you...

1674
01:48:45.842 --> 01:48:48.001
here on the Salt Flats,
Sportsman of the Year...

1675
01:48:48.011 --> 01:48:51.514
because we figured nobody has ever
traveled as far as you have...

1676
01:48:51.682 --> 01:48:53.182
to be here for Speed Week.

1677
01:48:53.350 --> 01:48:57.019
So normally, we would present
a trophy or something like that...

1678
01:48:57.187 --> 01:49:00.773
but considering your case, we thought
a few extra dollars would be appreciated...

1679
01:49:00.941 --> 01:49:02.650
so we passed the hat around.

1680
01:49:06.071 --> 01:49:08.239
Oh, my goodness.

1681
01:49:10.492 --> 01:49:13.035
All I know is...

1682
01:49:13.203 --> 01:49:14.870
Oh!

1683
01:49:25.716 --> 01:49:28.259
Well, thank you all.

1684
01:49:28.427 --> 01:49:31.929
Thank you all very much.

1685
01:49:32.097 --> 01:49:35.433
I'm sorry. I don't know what to say.

1686
01:49:36.226 --> 01:49:39.270
Oh, dear. It's quite overwhelming,
you know?

1687
01:49:39.438 --> 01:49:42.398
It's 25-years' dream to come here.

1688
01:49:44.860 --> 01:49:49.238
Well, I should try to justify
your respect...

1689
01:49:49.406 --> 01:49:51.949
and, you know...

1690
01:49:52.117 --> 01:49:56.203
the original speed of my old bike
was 54 miles an hour.

1691
01:49:58.915 --> 01:50:03.210
Now today I'm hoping to,
you know, improve it a little.

1692
01:50:30.113 --> 01:50:32.114
Next is Burt Munro...

1693
01:50:32.282 --> 01:50:36.869
all the way from Invercargill, New Zealand.

1694
01:50:37.037 --> 01:50:40.873
Burt Munro's entry was
approved just yesterday.

1695
01:50:47.047 --> 01:50:49.131
Huh? Come on, tighten it up.

1696
01:50:49.299 --> 01:50:51.133
- Burt, where'd you get this stuff?
- What?

1697
01:50:51.301 --> 01:50:54.762
- I said, where'd you get this stuff?
- Oh, I tore an old electric blanket apart...

1698
01:50:54.930 --> 01:50:56.806
and got the asbestos cloth out of it.

1699
01:50:56.973 --> 01:50:59.350
- Got those heart pills?
- You okay?

1700
01:50:59.518 --> 01:51:02.978
- Better take one. Yeah.
- Yeah. They're almost ready.

1701
01:51:03.146 --> 01:51:05.898
Guys, come on, let's go.

1702
01:51:06.066 --> 01:51:10.236
The bottle says that they may cause
drowsiness. Do not operate machinery.

1703
01:51:10.404 --> 01:51:12.988
- I know that.
- You're not supposed to take two of them.

1704
01:51:13.156 --> 01:51:15.741
One for me, one for the old girl.

1705
01:51:15.909 --> 01:51:19.203
Nitroglycerine. Make it go faster.

1706
01:51:19.371 --> 01:51:21.163
Have some of this, love.

1707
01:51:25.252 --> 01:51:26.836
There you go.

1708
01:51:32.801 --> 01:51:33.884
Yeah. We're almost there.

1709
01:51:34.052 --> 01:51:36.512
All right. Here we go.
Oh, let's do it.

1710
01:51:36.680 --> 01:51:37.805
- Your goggles, huh?
- What?

1711
01:51:37.973 --> 01:51:41.016
- Your goggles. Put your goggles on.
- Calm down. For goodness' sake.

1712
01:51:43.812 --> 01:51:45.020
- Come on.
- No, I can't.

1713
01:51:45.981 --> 01:51:49.775
I can't get my leg in because
of the asbestos cloth on it.

1714
01:51:50.986 --> 01:51:52.486
Okay.

1715
01:51:56.533 --> 01:51:58.742
Let me take it off.

1716
01:51:58.910 --> 01:52:02.788
- Well, what about your leg and the heat?
- Screw it. I've got a spare one.

1717
01:52:04.374 --> 01:52:06.584
- All right, Burt.
- Yeah?

1718
01:52:06.751 --> 01:52:08.210
Get those goggles on.

1719
01:52:08.378 --> 01:52:09.879
- You all right?
- Fine.

1720
01:52:10.046 --> 01:52:12.548
All right. You know the way.
Make sure you come back.

1721
01:52:12.716 --> 01:52:13.883
Come on, let's go!

1722
01:52:14.050 --> 01:52:16.552
All right, push!

1723
01:52:16.720 --> 01:52:18.554
All right! Come on, fellas, push faster!

1724
01:52:18.722 --> 01:52:20.389
All right, Burt!

1725
01:52:20.557 --> 01:52:21.807
Keep running!

1726
01:52:23.059 --> 01:52:24.894
Good luck!

1727
01:52:25.061 --> 01:52:27.021
Keep it straight, okay?

1728
01:52:28.273 --> 01:52:31.066
There you go, Burt!
Come on, go!

1729
01:52:31.234 --> 01:52:33.152
Let's go, Burt!

1730
01:52:36.156 --> 01:52:37.531
Woo-hoo!

1731
01:52:37.699 --> 01:52:39.533
Come on, Burt!

1732
01:52:39.701 --> 01:52:41.869
You can do it, Burt!

1733
01:52:42.037 --> 01:52:44.121
He's got no parachute
and he's got no brakes.

1734
01:53:02.974 --> 01:53:05.434
158.647.

1735
01:53:05.602 --> 01:53:09.438
Mile 1: 158.647 miles per hour.

1736
01:53:09.606 --> 01:53:10.689
Go, Burt!

1737
01:53:10.857 --> 01:53:13.234
- Come on!
- Go, Burt!

1738
01:53:13.401 --> 01:53:15.611
- Make us proud, honey!
- Burt!

1739
01:53:30.627 --> 01:53:32.711
167.921.

1740
01:53:32.879 --> 01:53:36.173
Mile 2: 167.921 miles per hour.

1741
01:53:36.341 --> 01:53:39.051
Crank it, Burt.
Come on. Go, go, go!

1742
01:53:39.219 --> 01:53:40.469
Come on, Burt!

1743
01:53:50.313 --> 01:53:54.358
Mile 3: 170.371 miles per hour.

1744
01:53:54.526 --> 01:53:56.068
Come on, come on, come on.

1745
01:54:07.455 --> 01:54:10.082
Mile 4: 172.485 miles per hour.

1746
01:54:10.250 --> 01:54:11.333
Go!

1747
01:54:11.501 --> 01:54:13.836
- Come on, Burt!
- That's the one! Come on, Burt!

1748
01:54:14.004 --> 01:54:15.462
Burt!

1749
01:54:15.630 --> 01:54:18.465
Mile 5: 183.694 miles per hour.

1750
01:54:37.819 --> 01:54:40.029
193.728.

1751
01:54:40.196 --> 01:54:43.365
Mile 6: 193.728 miles per hour.

1752
01:54:51.583 --> 01:54:53.626
Come on, Burt! You can do it!
Come on, Burt!

1753
01:54:53.793 --> 01:54:55.377
Come on, Burt!

1754
01:54:55.545 --> 01:54:58.922
Mile 7: 194.211 miles per hour.

1755
01:54:59.090 --> 01:55:02.968
- Come on, Burt!
- Holy moly! Come on!

1756
01:55:46.846 --> 01:55:48.013
What is it?

1757
01:55:48.181 --> 01:55:50.599
201 .851.

1758
01:55:50.767 --> 01:55:55.604
Mile 8: 201 .851 miles per hour.

1759
01:56:03.113 --> 01:56:05.739
Ladies and gentlemen, a new record...

1760
01:56:05.907 --> 01:56:10.494
201 .851 miles per hour.

1761
01:56:12.956 --> 01:56:15.040
Burt, I hope you're gonna stop soon.

1762
01:56:15.208 --> 01:56:18.001
- He's going back! Back.
- Back where?

1763
01:56:18.169 --> 01:56:19.769
Back to whatever planet he came from...

1764
01:56:19.879 --> 01:56:22.798
because he sure as hell
ain't from this one!

1765
01:57:16.060 --> 01:57:18.020
I really did toast my leg.

1766
01:57:23.651 --> 01:57:27.696
I did it. I did it.

1767
01:57:57.018 --> 01:58:00.938
Tom, can you get that?
My hands are wet.

1768
01:58:04.818 --> 01:58:06.109
Hello.

1769
01:58:06.277 --> 01:58:07.986
This is the United States calling.

1770
01:58:08.154 --> 01:58:11.240
I have a collect call from Mr. Burt Munro.
Will you accept the charge?

1771
01:58:11.407 --> 01:58:13.075
Mom, it's Burt calling collect!

1772
01:58:13.243 --> 01:58:15.536
It is? Accept the call.
Accept the call.

1773
01:58:15.703 --> 01:58:18.580
- My mom said we can accept the call.
- Go ahead, sir.

1774
01:58:18.748 --> 01:58:20.290
Hello, Tom, is that you?

1775
01:58:20.458 --> 01:58:24.086
- Yes.
- It's me, Burt. I did it, Tom.

1776
01:58:24.254 --> 01:58:27.881
- She's the world's fastest Indian!
- She is?

1777
01:58:28.049 --> 01:58:32.427
Dad. Dad. He did it. Burt did it.

1778
01:58:32.595 --> 01:58:34.429
He set a new record.

1779
01:58:49.404 --> 01:58:51.280
- Hi!
- Hey!

1780
01:58:51.447 --> 01:58:53.657
- How are you?
- Hey!

1781
01:58:53.825 --> 01:58:54.825
You did it!

1782
01:58:54.993 --> 01:58:57.619
Hi, Franklin. Jeff, thanks a lot, mate.

1783
01:58:57.787 --> 01:59:00.372
- Welcome home, Burt.
- Hello, George.

1784
01:59:00.540 --> 01:59:03.625
Oh, my goodness, you've made
this space look spiffy, mate.

1785
01:59:03.793 --> 01:59:05.127
- You done us proud!
- Yeah!

1786
01:59:05.295 --> 01:59:06.628
You put Invercargill on the map.

1787
01:59:06.796 --> 01:59:09.923
- Well, I reckon so, yeah.
- So, what have you got planned now?

1788
01:59:10.091 --> 01:59:12.011
Well, right now I've got
a lot of work to do...

1789
01:59:12.135 --> 01:59:14.511
if I'm to get back to Bonneville
next year, you know?

1790
01:59:14.679 --> 01:59:16.805
So more early mornings, then.

1791
01:59:16.973 --> 01:59:19.975
Yeah. More early mornings.
Hello, love.

1792
01:59:20.143 --> 01:59:23.395
- Welcome home.
- Nice to be back.

1793
01:59:23.563 --> 01:59:25.731
- Hello, Tom.
- Hi, Burt.

1794
01:59:25.899 --> 01:59:29.067
How are you, son?
Good to see you.

1795
01:59:29.235 --> 01:59:30.485
You're growing up a bit, huh?

1796
01:59:31.821 --> 01:59:33.780
I looked after your lemon tree,
like you told me.

1797
01:59:33.948 --> 01:59:36.825
You did, yeah. It's looking good too.

1798
01:59:36.993 --> 01:59:39.202
Yeah, it's beautiful.

1799
01:59:39.370 --> 01:59:41.663
- I fed the chickens.
- You did?

1800
01:59:41.831 --> 01:59:44.666
- And Mom cooked all the eggs.
- Oh, yeah? They taste good?

1801
01:59:44.834 --> 01:59:46.668
- Yep.
- Yeah. Hey, have you got the key?

1802
01:59:46.836 --> 01:59:48.670
- Here it is.
- All right, thanks.

1803
01:59:48.838 --> 01:59:50.797
- I took care of it.
- I knew you would.

1804
01:59:50.965 --> 01:59:53.508
- How fast did you go?
- Oh, mighty fast.

1805
01:59:53.676 --> 01:59:55.761
On one of my runs,
I did over 200 miles an hour.

1806
01:59:55.929 --> 01:59:59.097
Whoa! What would happen if you
opened your mouth at that speed?

1807
01:59:59.265 --> 02:00:01.975
Well, you'd blow the backside
out of your pants, I reckon.

1808
02:00:04.020 --> 02:00:06.188
All right. Let's see.

1809
02:00:06.356 --> 02:00:11.526
Ah! Nice to be home,
back in my shed.

